<HEADLINE> Albright Says NATO Needs Patience With War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Medeleine Albright said here Monday that the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) needs "patience and pereverance" over the air
strikes against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
After NATO foreign ministers had their special meeting on
Kosovo crisis at the NATO headquarters in Brussels, Albright told
reporters that "what has become evident with the military campaign
is that it is systematically biding into and destroying the
machine of repression."
</P>
<P>
The whole campaign "requires patience and perseverance and I am
sure that in the long run or in the medium run even that he (Mr.
Milosevic) is going to be feeling this."
</P>
<P>
Reporters have been told there was no plans of ground troops
deployment. After the special ministerial meeting, reporters were
also told that the 19 foreign ministers of the alliance did not
talk about matters concerning ground troops. But some journalists
wondered if the ministers privately discussed certain aspects of
such deployment.
</P>
<P>
Asked if she had discussions on this subject and if the NATO
would change its policy when some turnaround situation would
emerge, Albright said it was not appropriate for her to reveal
anything about any topics she discussed with her counterpart
ministers.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously, we are looking at the whole situation very
carefully, having very open and frank discussions as we are
dealing with this common problem and the question about turnaround
all that I suggest you ask the military," she told an ABC
correspondent at a news briefing after the NATO ministerial
meeting.
</P>
<P>
"Now, instead of diplomacy backed by the threat of force, we
must use diplomacy in support of force," Albright told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"Thus far, we have damaged but not destroyed his (Mr.
Milosevic) capability. Again and again, Milosevic has raised the
stakes. He is willing to take additional damage, and we must be
willing to bring additional power to bear," she said.
</P>
<P>
"NATO operations will continue until our conditions are met,"
she added.
</P>
<P>
During its special meeting, NATO issued a 15-point statement
including five-point demands to Yugoslavia:
</P>
<P>
- ensure a verifiable stop to all military action and the
immediate ending of violence and repression;
</P>
<P>
- ensure the withdrawal from Kosovo of the military, police and
paramilitary forces;
</P>
<P>
- agree to the stationing in Kosovo of an international
military presence;
</P>
<P>
- agree to the unconditional and safe return of all refugees
and displaced persons and unhindered access to them by
humanitarian aid organizations;
</P>
<P>
- provide credible assurance of his willingness to work on the
basis of the Rambouillet Accords in the establishment of a
political framework agreement for Kosovo in conformity with
international law and the Charter of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
NATO also said in the statement that it shares a common
interest with Russia in reaching a political solution to the
crisis in Kosovo and wants to work constructively with Russia.
</P>
<P>
Albright will meet Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov in Oslo
on Tuesday in bid to "bridge differences" in U.S.-Russian ties
over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"We must also keep trying to engage with Russia. Clearly, it is
in Moscow's interest as well as our own that Russia be part of the
solution," she told reporters this afternoon at a news briefing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
