<HEADLINE> Ghana,  Nigeria dominate drug trafficking scene: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Franklin Asamoah Mensah, a United
Nations Drug Control Program (UNDCP) officer said in Accra Monday
that Ghanaian and Nigerian drug trafficking networks continue to
dominate the drug scene.
</P>
<P>
 He said statistics from those arrested from the sub-region,
Europe and North America also indicate that drug couriers of a
variety of west African nationalities are being used to diversify
and subsequently dodge traditional courier profiles, the Ghana
News Agency quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
 Mensah was speaking at the opening of a five-day workshop on
the assessment of the drug situation in Ghana. It is aimed, among
other things, at finding modalities to check drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
 It is also meant to train personnel who will in turn train
others to go into the field to undertake an assessment of drug
abuse and illicit trafficking.
</P>
<P>
 The workshop is organized by the Dakar-based UNDCP regional
office for west and central Africa and is attended by participants
from Ghana and Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
 Mensah said there is limited reliable data on drug
cultivation, production, manufacture, trafficking and abuse and
this is a major constraint when trying to assess the drug
situation in most African countries.
</P>
<P>
 He said the workshop is therefore to discuss the problem of
data and avoid delaying potentially needed actions.
</P>
<P>
Mensah said any selection of "demand reduction strategy"
within a country should be based on assessment of the prevailing
drug abuse problem.
</P>
<P>
He said cannabis is the most prevalent in west Africa and its
main producers are still assumed to be Ghana and Nigeria followed
by Senegal and Cote d' Ivoire.
</P>
<P>
 Initially four countries in west Africa -- Cote d'Ivoire,
Ghana, Nigeria and Senegal -- had expressed to the UNDCP the
necessity to gauge the drug abuse situation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
