<HEADLINE> Israel Holds Ceremony to Mark Holocaust </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Israel Monday held a ceremony
in Jerusalem to mark the Holocaust Martyrs' and Heroes'
Remembrance Day.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony was held in the Yad Vashem Museum, which is
dedicated to perpetuating the memory of the 6 million Jews who
perished in the Holocaust in the World War II.
</P>
<P>
Israeli President Ezer Weizman, Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu and other dignitaries took part in the one-hour
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the ceremony, Weizman said the Jewish people will
never forget the Holocaust and will not let it happen again.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu contended that if the state of Israel were
established before World War II, the Holocaust might have been
avoided.
</P>
<P>
He said Israel must remain strong in the future so as to ensure
the security of the Jewish people.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister also mentioned the 112 refugees from the
warring Serbian province of Kosovo, who arrived in Israel on
Monday. He said it is Israel's moral obligation to take in Kosovo
refugees and provide them with humanitarian aid.
</P>
<P>
During the ceremony, six people were chosen to kindle the
memorial flames. They represent the Holocaust survivors who
settled in Israel.
</P>
<P>
The memorial activities, which began at the sunset of Monday,
will continue to Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Sirens will sound throughout the country for two minutes on
Tuesday morning, when traffic will come to a halt and people will
stand for two minutes in silent tribute to the memory of the
Holocaust victims.
</P>
<P>
And a wreath-laying ceremony at the Yad Vashem Museum will
also be held on Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
