<BODY>
<HEADLINE> survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 12 (Xinhua) -- A Ministry of Health (MOH) survey
in Ghana has identified Northern and Upper West regions as
trachoma-endemic areas.
</P>
<P>
Trachoma is a major cause of blindness.
</P>
<P>
The survey commissioned in 1996 and conducted at Daboya in the
West Gonja district of the Northern region revealed that 23.6
percent of the people have "active trachoma", which makes the
disease a public health problem, the Ghana News Agency (GNA)
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Dr Sylvester Anemana, Northern Regional Director of Health
Services who announced this at the opening of a four-day trachoma
assessment training workshop in Tamale Monday, said further
surveys are needed in the Northern,
</P>
<P>
Upper East and Upper West regions to determine trachoma
prevalence and control.
</P>
<P>
The four-day workshop organized by the MOH for 25 eye nurses
from Northern and Upper West regions will discuss "community
identification and mobilization for trachoma", "examine the eye
for trachoma" and "trachoma grading and reliability test".
Dr Anemana said under the medium-term health strategy, trachoma
and other endemic diseases would be drastically controlled.
Trachoma alone afflicts about 150 million people, he said, and
expressed the hope that through the active participation of
community health volunteers, the disease can be controlled in
Ghana.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Dr David Adiepenah, Northern regional
opthamologist, said trachoma, also known as the "forgotten
disease", plagues most rural dwellers, many of whom fail to report
for treatment. He said the MOH, in conjunction with the World
Health Organization's trachoma initiative and non-governmental
organizations, has set the year 2020 as the target for the
disease's complete eradication.
</P>
<P>
Dr Adiepenah said the fastest and economic way to achieve this
 objective "is by fighting the disease at where it is". Mr George
Ziniel, Regional Chairman of the Ghana Red Cross Society, said the
Swiss Red Cross Society has promised to equip the eye clinic at
the Tamale Regional hospital with a microscope to help in the
fight against trachoma. 
</P>
</TEXT>
