<HEADLINE> Angola Condemns NATO's Military Interference in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Robert de Almeida, Speaker of the
Angolan Parliament Monday condemned NATO's military interference
in Yugoslavia's affairs.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the 130th convention of the Inter-Parliamentary
Union in Brussels, Belgium, Almeida said that the U.S.,
Britain-headed NATO is acting on a "unilateral decision", the
offician Angola News Agency Angog reported.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time the Southern African country expresses
its stance on the NATO military action over Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Angog quoted the Angolan leader as saying at the Brussels
meeting that NATO is creating a dangerous example in "denying the
U.N. role in international affairs" and jumping the international
order based on the principle of respect for a nation's
sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
Almeida said the Balkan issues must be dealt with through
serious and authorized mediation, and that in this regard, full
consideration must be given to the causes of the issues and to the
interests of the parties concerned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
