<HEADLINE> Namibia Sells 14 Tons of Elephant Tusk: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Namibia has made millions of
U.S. dollars after selling about 14 tons of ivory to Japanese
buyers, Southern African Broadcasting Association quoted a senior
Namibian official as reporting Monday.
</P>
<P>
Tangeni Erkanae, permanent Secretary for Environment, said that
his country, together with Botswana and Zimbabwe, had agreed price
information would be kept secret until the last Southern African
auction next week.
</P>
<P>
Erkanae did not give the exact amount of money from the ivory
sale either.
</P>
<P>
The sale, monitored by officials of the Convention on
International Trade in Endangered Species, was held behind closed
doors at a hotel in Windhoek, the capital of Namibia, informed
sources said.
</P>
<P>
A Namibian newspaper said that one kilogram of elephant tusk
can fetch up to 500 U.S. dollars, depending on quality.
</P>
<P>
It quoted a source who attended Friday's auction as saying that
some Namibian ivory was sold for as little as 66 dollars per
kilogram due to low quality.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese buyers, whose country handles up to 70 tons of
ivory yearly, are in Zimbabwe, where they are expected to buy up
to 20 tons of ivory Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
