<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Set up State-Owned TV Station </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania plans to launch
the country' s first state-owned television station in July, the
Chairman of the Tanzania Broadcasting Commission (TBC), Mark
Bomani, said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The broadcasting services of the national station will first
start in the capital Dar es Salaam and its neighboring Coast
Region, then gradually extend to other parts of the country,
Bomani told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
At present, all television stations in the country are
privately owned and the government has been facing financial
constraints in starting a television station.
</P>
<P>
The TBC chairman also called on local and foreign investors to
come forward and cooperate with local owners of television and
radio stations to broaden their services in the country,
especially in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
He urged television and radio station to create their own
programs in Kiswahili language or English, saying that
broadcasting too many foreign programs are eroding Tanzanian
cultural norms.
</P>
<P>
Bomani said although there are many good programs like news
bulletins and special reports about the country's economy,
politics and social activities, the programs need to improve as a
number of them are terrible, threatening the growth of the new
generation.
</P>
<P>
Private radio and television stations began to be licensed to
operate in Tanzania at the beginning of 1994, but they are not
allowed to cover more than 25 percent of the country's territory
according to the 1993 Broadcasting Act.
</P>
<P>
At a workshop for television and radio broadcasters held in the
central region of Morogoro last week, Bomani urged the authorities
to review the act and raise the restriction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
