<HEADLINE> Iraq Demands Vaccines for Animal Disease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Iraq sent a letter to the
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan on Monday demanding urgent
supplies of vaccines for foot and mouth disease (FMD) rampant
among animals in the country, the Iraqi News Agency INA reported.
</P>
<P>
The letter, sent by Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed Saeed
al-Sahhaf, said the Iraqi government is in urgent need of these
vaccines as FMD is threatening livestock in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Sahhaf said the supplies of the vaccines must be distributed
according to the national vaccination plan worked out by expertise
in Iraq to exterminate this epidemic.
</P>
<P>
He added all Iraqi animals might be exposed to further
epidemics in the light of reports warning of new infections in
adjacent countries due to the lack of vaccines against FMD.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has demanded the U.N. compensation for its citizens for
their losses caused by the spread of FMD among livestock which
led to the shortage of red meat and dairy.
</P>
<P>
During the 1970s Iraq set up a strategic vaccination project
capable of producing 12 million doses annually for preventing
animal diseases.
</P>
<P>
The project was suspended due to the 1991 Gulf War and most of
its production and diagnosis equipment were destroyed in 1996 by
the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) in charge of eliminating
Iraq's weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi media have reported that some 1.5 million heads of
cattle and sheep have died of FMD so far this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
