<DOCNO> XIE19990413.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese, Bangladeshi Leaders Agree to Enhance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Chinese leader Li Peng
exchanged views with Bangladeshi Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina
Monday on international and regional issues of common concern, and
they agreed to further enhance bilateral relations between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
During their talks Monday evening, Li Peng, chairman of the
Standing Committee of the National People's Congress of China,
informed Hasina of the Chinese government's views on
multi-polarization, diversification and economic globalization.
</P>
<P>
He said that China attaches importance to the friendly
relations of good-neighborliness with its neighboring countries,
including Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
China is now focusing on economic development, and therefore
needs stability at home and wishes to have a peaceful environment
in the world, especially in the areas surrounding the country, he
said.
</P>
<P>
China appreciates the positive contributions that Bangladesh
has made in promoting regional stability and world peace by
pursuing a foreign policy of neutrality and non-alignment, said
the Chinese leader.
</P>
<P>
Welcoming Li's current visit to Bangladesh, Hasina said that
Bangladesh has received uninterrupted assistance from China in its
national economic development, which the Bangladeshi people will
never forget.
</P>
<P>
She said that the major challenge facing the country is to
eradicate poverty, and hence she wishes to develop economic and
trade cooperation with friendly countries including China, so as
to promote the economic development of the country.
</P>
<P>
Both Li and Hasina also agreed that it is imperative to enhance
 solidarity and cooperation among developing countries, especially
at a time when the world situation is undergoing profound changes,
and when opportunities and challenges coexist.
</P>
<P>
Noting that both China and Bangladesh are located in Asia, and
are developing countries, they agreed that to develop long-term
friendship relations of good-neighborliness is in conformity with
the long-term and fundamental interest of both countries.
</P>
<P>
Li, who last visited this South Asian nation in 1989 as
premier, arrived here on Monday afternoon on a two-day goodwill
official visit to Bangladesh, the fifth leg of his six-nation
European and Asian tour. 
</P>
