<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Supports Establishment of Palestinian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami on Monday voiced Tehran's support for establishing an
independent Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian people's historical rights should be respected,
said Khatami while meeting with Farouk Kadoumy, Chairman of the
Palestine Liberation Organization (PLO) Political Department, the
Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that the establishment of an independent Palestinian
state would be a prelude to restoring the rights of the oppressed
Palestinian people and liberation of the entire holy land of
Palestine.
</P>
<P>
Palestine belongs to the Palestinian people, Khatami said,
adding that nobody has the right to offer anything on behalf of
the Palestinian people or compromise their principles.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Palestine's destiny cannot be determined
without the votes of all Palestinians, including Muslims, Jews
and Christians.
</P>
<P>
Iran condemned the compromising process in the Middle East,
and the compromise is a vain process from legal, ideological and
analytical points of view and would not be effective in reality,
said Khatami.
</P>
<P>
Khatami expressed hope that justice would prevail not only in
Palestine, but elsewhere in the world and said that justice might
be suppressed but would not be eliminated.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that the Islamic Republic of Iran would never
recognize the Israeli regime and it believes that usurpation,
aggression and assassination do not reserve any right for
anybody.
</P>
<P>
Khatami noted that defending the Palestinian people's rights
and struggles, and condemning the aggressions on them have been
intermingled with Iran's Islamic revolution.
</P>
<P>
The bond between Iranian revolution and people and
Palestinian people is historical and cannot be broken easily, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Iran and the Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) have been strained after the PAN signed a peace accord
with Israel in the United States last year.
</P>
<P>
Kadoumy thanked Iran for its support for the Palestinian
people and briefed Khatami on the latest developments in the
Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Previous experience has shown that Israel is not for peace and
the U.S., which has played a key role in creation of the Israeli
entity, is incapable of forcing the regime to withdraw from the
occupied lands, he said.
</P>
<P>
Kadoumy, who arrived here on Friday, also noted that
Israel would continue its policy of developing Jewish settlements,
devastating Palestinian homes and occupying their residential
buildings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990413.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Education Coverage Doubles in Ethiopia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Education of
Ethiopia said Monday that the national education coverage has
doubled over the last six years.
</P>
<P>
Public relation head of the ministry, Shimeles Letike, said
that the national education coverage which was only 19.6 percent
in 1993 has currently reached 42 percent, the Ethiopian News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Shimeles said the five-year National Education Development
Program launched in 1997 aims at increasing the over-all education
coverage to 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
"In the light of the progress made so far there could be a
significant rise beyond the targeted coverage within the next
three years," he said.
</P>
<P>
Shimeles said the National Education Development Program has
given special attention to the rural parts of the country, adding
that efforts are also being made to balance education distribution
in urban and rural areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
