<HEADLINE> Ghana Backs Russia's Involvement in Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
Crisis
</P>
<P>
 NAIROBI, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Ghana's President Jerry J.
Rawlings Monday welcomed United States Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright's call on Russia to play a role in finding a
peaceful solution to the conflict in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
 "Mrs Albright's invitation to Russia is in the right
direction," Rawlings said in Accra, adding that NATO's bombing is
creating a lot of discomfort and could escalate and spill into
Albania, a Ghana News Agency (GNA) reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
 Rawlings who has called for a negotiated settlement to the
crisis in Yugoslavia said Belgrade has already been made aware
that it cannot carry out "the murderous campaign" it did in
Bosnia a few years back.
</P>
<P>
He made these points when a Japanese envoy called on him at
the Castle, Osu, to seek Ghana's support for his bid to become
Director-General of United Nations Education and Cultural
Organization (UNESCO).
</P>
<P>
 Koichiro Matsuura, Japanese ambassador in France, said his
candidature has the full backing of the government of Japan.
</P>
<P>
 Matsuura, who was in Ghana between 1961 and 1963, spoke about
his country and said from a humble beginning "Japan now has the
capacity and the will to help other countries."
</P>
<P>
 Rawlings said several candidates have emerged for the post
which is now being occupied by Mr Federico Mayor of Spain.
</P>
<P>
He told Mr Matsuura: "among the various candidates we find you
one of the most capable. Your chances are as good as those of the
others."
</P>
<P>
Rawlings said in seeking to create a just world, the role of
UNESCO is vital in view of the need to step up its education
programs. "The role of UNESCO cannot be ruled out." 
</P>
