<HEADLINE> UK Offers $70m to Back Rwandan Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Britain promised Monday to offer
about 70 million U.S. dollars to help boost the small central
African country's budget in the coming 10 years.
</P>
<P>
An agreement was signed by the visiting British Secretary of
State for International Cooperation, Clare Short and Rwanda's
Vice-President, Major General Paul Kagame.
</P>
<P>
The pledged assistance will serve to help Rwanda to enhance good
 governance, conflict resolution, human resources, education, and
health services, a story by the Rwanda News Agency reaching here
Monday said.
</P>
<P>
According to Rwandan Minister of Finance, Britain has already
disbursed 50 million U.S. dollars pledged during last June
Stockholm (Sweden) Round- Table of donors, and 10 million more to
the Trust Fund.
</P>
<P>
This Monday, Clare Short also signed an agreement with Kaberuka
 equivalent to eight million dollars in support of Rwanda's
revenue collection office, the Rwanda Revenue Authority (RRA).
</P>
<P>
''We hope that the signing of this protocol will seal our
determination to extend it to other areas of cooperation,''
highlighted Kagame.
</P>
<P>
Today's British aid to Rwanda marked a turning point in the
disbursement of foreign assistance to Rwanda pledged in Stockholm,
Sweden, in June of last year, the Rwanda News Agency story said.
</P>
<P>
With the outbreak of war in Congo (K), donor countries froze
their financial aid to Rwanda for fear that it might be used for
the military campaign of its troops in Congo.
</P>
<P>
However, Britain supports the current mediation efforts aimed
at brokering a peace deal in Congo, Short told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
''We want a just peace which includes security concerns of
Rwanda which we fully understand,'' she underscored. 
</P>
</TEXT>
