<HEADLINE> Israeli Soldier Killed in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 12 (Xinhua) -- An Israeli soldier was killed
and several others wounded Monday afternoon by a roadside bomb
in south Lebanon, Lebanese security sources said.
</P>
<P>
The bomb was detonated on a road near the Israeli-held
Beaufort Castle position just on the verge of the Israeli
occupied border zone in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of
God, has claimed responsibility for the attack.
</P>
<P>
In response, Israeli artillery forces bombarded the villages
near the Beaufort Castle which are believed to be hideouts for
Hezbollah guerrillas. There has been no immediate reports of
casualties.
</P>
<P>
The blast raised to eight the number of the Israeli
soldiers killed in south Lebanon since the start of this
year.
</P>
<P>
In February, a total of seven Israelis, including a
general, was killed during the Hezbollah separate ambushes.
</P>
<P>
The mounting Israeli losses rekindled the heated debate inside
Israel over a withdrawal from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-proclaimed security zone in south Lebanon
in 1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from
Lebanese guerillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Lebanon's resistance movement spearheaded by
Hezbollah has been fighting to oust Israeli forces out of
the country.
</P>
<P>
In another development which follows the killing of the Israeli
soldier, Hezbollah announced that one of its fighters was killed
during his operation against an Israeli position inside the
border enclave. But it did not provide any details. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
