<HEADLINE> Meeting on Land-Mine Ban Expected in Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The first meeting of the signatory
states of the Ottawa Convention on the Prohibition of Use,
Storage, Production and Transfer of Anti-Personnel Land-Mines and
their Destruction will be held in Maputo between May 3 to 7, a
senior official said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Leonardo Simao said at a press conference here
that the meeting will discuss ways of offering help to land mine
victims, finding access for them to re-enter the society.
</P>
<P>
Simao said that Secretary General of the United Nations Kofi
Annan, the heads of the Organization of African Unity, the
Southern African Development Community, and about 1,000 leaders
from 150 countries and organizations have been invited to the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Ottawa convention required that the signatory states should
clear all the land mines on their land within 10 years, but for
countries which lack the means to do so, like Mozambique, help
from international community is needed, he said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will be the largest such meeting hosted by
Mozambique since its independence in 1975, Simao said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
