<HEADLINE> Solana Says Yugoslavia Must be Integrated by Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Secretary-General of the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), Javier Solana, told reporters
here Monday that the countries of the Former Yugoslavia and their
neighbors must be brought into the European mainstream.
</P>
<P>
"It is important that we begin to look beyond the crisis in
Kosovo," Solana told a news briefing after NATO foreign ministers
finish their special meeting here at NATO headquarters in
Brussels.
</P>
<P>
"They must all be able to enjoy the same peace, security and
prosperity as the other countries of Europe," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The years of confrontation must come to an end in southeastern
Europe or there will be no future for its people," the NATO chief
said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the military bloc issued a 15-point statement during
its special ministerial meeting of the North Atlantic Council, the
NATO's decision-making body. "NATO's air strikes will be pursued
until President Milosevic accedes to the demands of the
international community. President Milosevic knows what he has to
do," the statement warned.
</P>
<P>
The 19 allies also insist on a five-point demands to
Yugoslavia, demonstrating their determination to keep the war
against Yugoslavia going on.
</P>
<P>
However, the chief of allies stressed their goal of going after
war for peace. "Today we confirmed that we will play a full part
in a comprehensive approach to stabilize this region. Such an
approach which should address the political, economic, security
and humanitarian aspects must involve a number of instiltutions
but NATO will have its role to play," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
