<HEADLINE> Schroeder Elected SPD Chairman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 12 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder
was elected with weaker support than expected the new chairman of
the ruling Social Democratic Party (SPD) by a special party
congress Monday in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder won 370 of the 487 valid votes, with 102 oppositions
and 15 abstentions. About 515 delegates of the SPD took part in
the congress.
</P>
<P>
One month after the surprise resignation of the popular SPD
traditionalist Oscar Lafontaine both as party chairman and finance
minister, Schroeder is to formally head the party.
</P>
<P>
The SPD has showed its ability to make responsible decision,
Schroeder said after the congress, adding that the cabinet
governed by the party could now go out of the hard time.
</P>
<P>
As an unopposed candidate for party chairman, Schroeder has got
the worst result in SPD's history since 1946. Nevertheless,
Schroeder was able to consolidate his power with the victory.
</P>
<P>
"There is a great deal written in the press that the party does
not love me, and I would say there is some truth to this,"
Schroeder admitted.
</P>
<P>
"What I want is something else, I want respect for my work and
your support for my job," he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier at the congress, the SPD delegates passed despite
opposition from the party pacifists a resolution backing NATO
strikes against Yugoslavia until Belgrade withdraws its troops
from Kosovo and allows the refugees to return home.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
