<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia Reiterates Support to Jordan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Saudi King Fahd Ibn
Abdul-Aziz Monday reiterated his country's firm support to Jordan
and its keenness on promoting ties with Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Fahd made the remarks at a regular weekly cabinet session held
in the Saudi Red Sea coastal city of Jeddah.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the Saudi cabinet reviewed the outcome of
talks between King Fahd and Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein
during the latter's recent visit to Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah paid a three-day state visit to the Gulf kingdom last
week as part of a Gulf tour that took him later to Oman and the
United Arab Emirates.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian officials have expressed satisfaction with the
visit. They hailed as "constructive and cordial" Abdullah's talks
with Fahd, which touched on bilateral ties and a number of other
issues of mutual concern.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral ties between Saudi Arabia and Jordan were affected by
Amman's siding with Iraq during the 1991 Gulf War triggered by
Iraq's invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia, which had been the largest donor for Jordan,
suspended its nearly 200 million U.S. dollars in annual economic
aid and cut its oil supply to the country after the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
In the past several years, the two Arab kingdoms have been
making efforts to amend the damaged ties, which saw a boost since
Jordanian King Hussein's death and Abdullah's succession to the
throne of the Hashemite Kingdom on February 7.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi government has sent several ministers to Jordan to
follow up closely the financial situation there and promised to
provide necessary help.
</P>
<P>
Riyadh has granted Jordan 250 million dollars since last
February, the Kuwait News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
It also deposited 450 million dollars at the Jordanian central
bank in an effort to help the Jordanian economy, the agency said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
