<HEADLINE> Trimble Says IRA Can Bring Peace by Decommissioning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Northern Ireland Assembly's first
minister David Trimble said on Monday the peace process in
Northern Ireland was now dependent on the commitment of republican
groups to turn their back on violence.
</P>
<P>
Trimble, who is also Ulster Unionist leader, told BBC Radio 4's
Today program the peace declaration issued two weeks ago had the
"potential" to work but questioned the republican's commitment to
the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Trimble said what was at stake was a question of whether Sinn
Fein leaders and the people for whom they speak were actually
committed to the agreement or not.
</P>
<P>
"But the question is whether the organizations for which they
speak are committed to the agreement and are prepared to turn
their back (on violence)," he said.
</P>
<P>
Trimble was speaking ahead of a week of renewed negotiations to
find a solution to the stalled process.
</P>
<P>
The pro-British Unionists refuse to form the assembly's
executive with Sinn Fein until the IRA begins decommissioning its
weapons. But Sinn Fein, the political wing of the IRA, insists
decommissioning is not a precondition laid out in last year's Good
Friday Agreement.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister Tony Blair and the his Irish counterpart
Bertie Ahern are expected to mount another attempt to restart the
peace process on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Most of the political parties involved will hold separate
meetings on Monday to formulate their opinions on the Hillsborough
declaration proposed by the two prime ministers.
</P>
<P>
Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam will lead discussions
between the pro-agreement parties on Tuesday and will be joined by
Irish Foreign Minister David Andrews and his Junior Minister Liz
O'Donnell. 
</P>
