<HEADLINE> Annan Regrets Afghan Taleban's Canceling of Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 12 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan on Monday expressed deep regrets over the canceling of
peace talks by Agfhanistan's warring party the Taleban.
</P>
<P>
The Taleban leadership decided over the week that they would
not resume the negotiations which had started in Ashkabad,
Turkmenistan, last month, which was under U.N. auspices.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by U.N. spokesman's office said "The
Secretary-General is concerned that this development will lead to
the intensification of fighting between the Taleban and the United
Front, thus inflicting more suffering on the people of Afghanistan
and more destruction in an already devastated country."
</P>
<P>
"The United Nations will resume consultations with the two
sides, as well as with other Afghans, interested Members States
to explore the scope for agreement on confidence-building measures
which might help to contain the current level of fighting and
might hopefully draw the two sides back to peaceful discussion,"
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The Afghan warring parties the Taleban and the opposition
alliance held peace talks last month in Ashkabad, Turkmenistan,
under the U.N. auspices. During the talks, the two sides agreed
in principle on the creation of a coalition government to
include all of the country's political forces. They also agreed
to continue their talks this month.  
</P>
