<HEADLINE> SADC Countries to Jointly Attract Investment: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 12 (Xinhua) -- South African Finance
Minister Trevor Manuel Monday expressed belief that the 14
Southern African Development Community (SADC) countries would make
joint efforts to attract investment.
</P>
<P>
SADC countries are likely to align their incentives to attract
investment, but this could take some time because of their
different needs and market conditions, Manuel told a media
briefing in Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
Manuel made the remarks when 11 members of the 14-nation
trading bloc are currently negotiating a free trade agreement,
which was the subject of a two-day conference organized by the
Trade and Industry Department of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Manuel noted that more effort was needed to minimize conflict
between SADC countries competing for the same investments and care
had to be taken to minimize market distortions.
</P>
<P>
He said the wars in Angola and the Democratic Republic of Congo
were hampering policy implementation within the SADC, adding war
represented the worst kind of tax on future generations because it
destroyed infrastructure and left countries with huge debts.
</P>
<P>
Mfundo Nkhulu, chief director of African trade relations in the
Trade and Industry Department, said it was hoped the the SADC free
trade agreement would be implemented at the beginning of next
year.
</P>
<P>
The SADC, established in 1992, consists of Angola, Botswana,
Zimbabwe, Lesotho, Malawi, Mozambique, Namibia, Swaziland,
Tanzania, Zambia, Mauritius, Democratic Republic of Congo,
Seychelles and South Africa. 
</P>
