<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Duma Postpones Yeltsin Impeachment Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Party leaders in Russia's State
Duma, lower house of parliament, agreed on Monday to put off
indefinitely a vote starting the impeachment process against
President Boris Yeltsin, planned for Thursday, the Agrarian Party
leader said.
</P>
<P>
Duma speaker Gennady Seleznyov told the press that a new date
would be set after the Duma adopted detailed voting rules and
other procedures. The party leaders form the majority of the
managing Duma Council, which will make a formal decision on the
postponement.
</P>
<P>
President Boris Yeltsin told the Russian parliament on Monday
that he opposed plans to postpone a vote in the State Duma lower
house, which was scheduled for Thursday to formally launch
impeachment proceedings against him, the Kremlin said.
</P>
<P>
"In the course of his telephone conversation with the Duma
speaker, Gennady Seleznyov, earlier today, the president
reiterated his position that the issue should either be considered
now or dropped for good," said a Kremlin spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Seleznyov said he believed the vote could hardly take place
before mid-May. He said a working group would begin drawing up
regulations on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Seleznyov and other parliamentary leaders have said that they
think it unwise to move ahead on impeachment when Russia is
opposing NATO air strikes on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov has urged lawmakers not to vote
for impeachment. In a television address on Saturday he said the
move risked destabilising the country.
</P>
<P>
The Communist-led Duma seeks to impeach Yeltsin on five charges,
including undermining the Soviet Union, dissolving the Soviet-era
parliament in 1993 and launching an ill-fated war in the rebel
region of Chechnya in 1994-96.
</P>
<P>
If any of these charges wins 300 votes in the 450-seat Duma, it
will go to the Constitutional Court and the Supreme Court for
examination. A final decision on impeachment would be up to the
Federation Council, the upper house of parliament.
</P>
<P>
Parliamentary experts say that only the Chechen charge has a
small chance of getting the required 300 votes in the Duma.
</P>
<P>
Analysts noted that some Duma leaders, headed by Seleznyov, had
suggested that the vote be put off because Yeltsin is spearheading
Moscow's opposition to NATO air strikes against Yugoslavia, an
issue which has consolidated feuding Russian political forces.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
