<DOCNO> XIE19990413.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-12 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Lebanon Takes Tax-Hikes as </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese new government, which
took office last December, finally tabled a bold measure Wednesday
to raise revenues by tax hikes, a sovereign remedy expected to
revitalize the ailing economy.
</P>
<P>
The tax increases, which includes a controversial 20-percent
more tax in gasoline, was announced on Wednesday night following a
weekly cabinet session along with the 1999 budget bill.
</P>
<P>
The bill pegged revenue for 1999 at 3.2 billion dollars, and
spending at 5.5 billion dollars, compared with the respective
figures of 2.9 billion dollars and 5.2 billion dollars for 1998.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that the increase in petrol price alone could
add at least 120 million U.S. dollars annually to the treasury
coffer.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government also decided to raise taxes on
non-essential imported commodities such as liquor, cigarettes,
flowers, jewelry, yachts, wrist watches, cheese, fireworks, cloths
and furs that are beyond the poor classes' consumption.
</P>
<P>
These sweeping tax increases on commodities would ensure
another 1.5 million dollars a month for the treasury income.
</P>
<P>
Information Minister Anwar Khalil has explained that the price
hikes were aimed at raising more revenues and thus meet the
targeted 1999 budget deficit of 40.2 percent of expenditures.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese economy is undergoing a record recession since the
end of the 1975-1990 civil war with public debt climbing to 18
billion dollars, among the highest in the world on the per capita
basis.
</P>
<P>
The budget deficit, which finished at 14 percent of gross
domestic product last year, though down from 24 percent in 1997,
is viewed by economists as dangerously massive.
</P>
<P>
The government headed by Salim Hoss attributed the main
responsibility to the haphazard spending in the post-war
reconstruction drive by the six cabinets under former Prime
Minister Rafik Hariri.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the government's austere economic policy, most
of the country's economists and politicians said this is a first
step in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
Former House Speaker Hussein Husseini hailed the budget bill as
"based on the country's true capacities."
</P>
<P>
He called on various sectors, including all economic and social
institutions and unions to support the government's efforts.
</P>
<P>
However, the bill provoked stiff opposition from the country's
largest trade union group General Labor Confederation (GLC), which
groups about 35,000 workers.
</P>
<P>
"We have incessantly counseled the government against this
(gasoline) tax. We have publicly warned that the gasoline price
is political sulphur but the government has turned a deaf ear,"
said GLC Chairman Abu Rizk.
</P>
<P>
The former Hariri government had also tried to raise revenues
by increasing gasoline price but abandoned in light of GLC's
protest threat and strong opposition of House Speaker Nabih Berri,
a long-time political rival of Hariri.
</P>
<P>
The union has again threatened to take to the street, saying
the gasoline tax will affect all classes and make unendurable
living conditions of the middle-income and low-income classes.
</P>
<P>
Political sources said that even if protests happened, it
would be of limited impact in view of the consensus reached among
President Emile Lahoud, Hoss and Berri on the budget bill.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet is now busy preparing a five-year plan, which aims
at eventually eliminating the budget deficit and bringing down
public debt, and will submit it along with the budget bill to the
parliament for debate which is expected to take place next month.
</P>
<P>
Some economists said the tax plan is of greater significance
than the budget bill because it would present a clearer view of
the government's economic policy in the next five years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
