<HEADLINE> Poll Delay May Harm Confidence in S. Africa: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Any delay in the upcoming
elections could negatively affect investor confidence in South
Africa, Finance Minister Trevor Manuel warned Monday.
</P>
<P>
International investors had already discounted the fact that
the election would take place and that irrational statements would
be made, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, the series of court actions by opposition parties
aimed at extending voting rights to South Africans abroad could
prove problematic if they caused a delay in the poll, Manuel said.
</P>
<P>
"By the end of June, in parts of the country it is almost
impossible to have people standing in queues. Winter sets in --
it's very very uncomfortable for people.
</P>
<P>
"You are then looking at a much later period (for the poll)."
</P>
<P>
Manuel said this would have a number of negative consequences,
including a delay in the next parliament session.
</P>
<P>
"The most important thing from our perspective is that the
election be allowed to proceed on June 2 and run its course,"
Manuel said.
</P>
<P>
Following a court ruling that South African prisoners should be
allowed to vote, opposition parties lodged law suits, demanding
the voting rights for those working or otherwise staying abroad at
the election day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
