<HEADLINE> Four-fifths of Zambia's Economy in Private Hands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- President Frederick Chiluba said
here Monday that more than 80 percent of Zambia's economy is now
in private hands.
</P>
<P>
Opening the 1999 Zambia-United Kingdom Cooperation Week,
Chiluba said that "we have in less than seven years brought an
economy which was 80 percent in the hands of the state to 180
degrees round to more than 80 percent in the private sector hands
today."
</P>
<P>
He said that British investment in Zambia has always been
significant. Today more and more British firms are investing in
Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Britain has for the past eight years maintained the top
position in investment in Zambia with pledges totalling 250
million U.S. dollars, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said Britain remains one of the largest bilateral aid donors
to Zambia and has been actively involved in the development of
zambia's health and education sectors, small and medium
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
He said, "many enterprising Zambians want an opportunity for
business not charity, we want more business as a country, not just
aid."
</P>
<P>
Chiluba said Zambia wants debt write-off because "it will give
us opportunity to develop and we are happy the UK has championed
the call for better terms on debt repayment."
</P>
<P>
He urged Britain to carry on the message to the meeting of the
G7 next june.
</P>
<P>
The trade value between the countries stood at about 100
million dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of British companies and Zambian enterprises are
participating in a fair of the UK-Zambia Cooperation Week.
</P>
<P>
During the week, cultural and sports events and seminars are
also held here. 
</P>
</TEXT>
