<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Disarmament Commission Opens 1999 Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Disarmament Commission opened its 1999 session here Monday with
focus on conventional weapons, nuclear-weapons-free zones and a
General Assembly special session.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening session, Jayantha Dhanapala,
under-secretary-general for disarmament affairs, said sustainable
disarmament had lagged far behind sustainable development, but the
Disarmament Commission had an opportunity to contribute to the
former by shedding light on common objectives, as well as on the
differences that divided States.
</P>
<P>
Dhanapala said the establishment of nuclear-weapon-free zones
challenged international diplomacy and yet, the nightmare of a
world full of "nuclear-weapon-full zones" should be a motivation
to continue the efforts.
</P>
<P>
As for the possible convening of a fourth special session of
the General Assembly devoted to disarmament, he said there was an
urgent need to weave the epochal international changes into the
multilateral disarmament order, but to seek end results when the
Commission's charge was to promote agreement on the agenda and
timing would be putting the cart before the horse.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of formulating conventional arms control
guidelines, he said advocacy on practical disarmament measures
need not compromise the right to self-defense nor draw attention
from nuclear disarmament.
</P>
<P>
Like development, disarmament was also a process, and one that
must be sustained over many years, pursued through many venues and
opened to contributions from many entities, he stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
