<HEADLINE> Clinton Visits Air Base to Back Troops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 12 (Xinhua) -- President Clinton Monday
visited Barksdale Air Force Base, which has been sending B-52 and
A-10 bombers on missions to Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Barksdale is home to the 2nd Bomb Wing, which has members
deployed in Europe as part of the NATO mission in Yugoslavia.
Clinton was meeting privately with air crews that recently
returned from flying combat missions over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
He called the plight of ethnic Albanian refugees "a human
tragedy that touches everyone," and said it is incumbent upon the
United States to stanch the crisis before it escalates into a
wider war.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said, "We would like to nip this conflict in the bud
before it destabilizes all of Europe. We don't want American
soldiers... to die on distant battlefields in large numbers."
</P>
<P>
Clinton was accompanied by Defense Secretary William Cohen;
Army Gen. Henry Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff;
and Sens. Mary Landrieu and John Breaux, D-La.
</P>
<P>
Cohen told reporters the NATO airstrikes are taking a toll on
Serb forces, lowering their morale and prompting some to desert.
</P>
<P>
He said there is "a growing consensus and a strong consensus"
in Congress for the current air campaign, and that the Clinton
administration will not consider the possibility of ground troops
since the NATO command has not requested them.
</P>
<P>
However, "should it become necessary, we'll take it under
advisement," Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton came to deliver a message of support to the men and
women in uniform and their families.
</P>
<P>
Upon his return to Washington, Clinton will gather House and
Senate leaders at the White House Monday night for a report on the
Kosovo situation.
</P>
<P>
National security spokesman David Leavy said Clinton expects to
review the air campaign and discuss an emergency appropriation to
finance the Kosovo mission. He will meet with a larger group of
lawmakers Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
So far, the president has faced relatively muted criticism over
his handling of the Kosovo operation and reliance on air power
amidst a growing refugee crisis caused by the warfare.
</P>
<P>
With Congress returning from a two-week recess Monday, that
dynamic could change as lawmakers challenge Clinton's
determination against ground forces. 
</P>
