<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets Close Mostly Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON April 12 (Xinhua) - Europe's major markets bounced back
in late trading on Monday as Wall Street recovered from early
falls, but ended largely in the minus column.
</P>
<P>
After sliding more than 70 points in the first 30 minutes of
trade, the Dow clambered back up. By the London close, the Wall
Street's benchmark was down only 1 point.
</P>
<P>
Cheered by the recound, the FTSE 100 ended down 31.6, or 0.5
percent, at 6441.2, having bottomed out at 6377.2 just after
midday.
</P>
<P>
A bearish mood had gripped London from the start of trade as
investors reacted to a profits warning from US computer giant
Compaq late Friday.
</P>
<P>
However, UK analysts said that fundamentals remain positive for
the London equity market, particularly after last week's wave of
rate cuts.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, the only major European bourse to close higher on
the session, trade continued to draw some upward momentum from
last week's half-percentage-point rate cut by the European Central
Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Xetra Dax index of leading shares closed up 33.6 points at
5167. However, trading was thin with one trader saying that
investors were not attracted by the German market with uncertainty
over the policies of the government, especially over wage
agreements.
</P>
<P>
Share prices closed slightly down in Paris in thin trading with
earlier losses largely recovered as Wall Street bounced back from
its opening declines.
</P>
<P>
The Cac-40 index, which at one point was down 50 points, closed
down 8 points at 4335. 
</P>
</TEXT>
