<DOCNO> XIE19990413.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Scientists Develop New Male Contraceptive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 12 (Xinhua) -- British scientists said Monday
they have developed a pill-patch combination method of
contraception for men.
</P>
<P>
The success of clinical trials using the method brings an
easy-to-take reversible male contraception a step closer, Dr Fred
Wu and colleagues, of Manchester Royal Infirmary, told the British
Endocrine Societies annual meeting.
</P>
<P>
The researchers carried out their trials on 23 local male
volunteers who took a progesterone hormone pill, while wearing a
body patch containing the sex hormone testosterone.
</P>
<P>
The volunteers were divided into three different groups,
receiving low, medium and high levels of the progesterone pill.
</P>
<P>
Most of the men in the high and medium groups showed no active
sperm after three months. When they stopped taking the pill, their
sperm counts gradually returned to normal.
</P>
<P>
The method has still to be optimized, but this work will lead
to a more user-acceptable method of male contraception, the
researchers believed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
