<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Asks U.N. Body to Determine Legal Consequences </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Russia Monday asked the
International court of Justice to determine the legal consequences
of NATO's military action in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Russia asked for the highest U.N. legal body's opinion in a
draft resolution submitted to the U.N. General Assembly committee
which deals with strengthening and upholding of the U.N. Charter.
</P>
<P>
The draft resolution said individual nations and regional
organizations cannot use force against sovereign states without
the authorization of the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
"No considerations, whether political, economic, military or of
any other kind, may be used to justify the threat or use of force
in violation of the Charter of the United Nations," the draft
resolution said.
</P>
<P>
It requested the international Court of Justice to give its
opinion on the legal consequences such unauthorized intervention
would have for the United Nations and for peace in the world.
</P>
<P>
Russia brought its position to the Security Council last month
and demanded an end to NATO's military strikes against Yugoslavia,
but it was blocked. 
</P>
</TEXT>
