<HEADLINE> Netherlands Continuing Support For Chinese Entry Into WTO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The Netherlands will continue to
support China's entry into the World Trade Organization (WTO) and
continue to criticise the EU's anti-dumping policy, the Dutch
Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of Economic Affairs Annemarie
Jorritsma said here today.
</P>
<P>
She made the remark at a press conference here this evening
where Jorritsma said that she has discussed bilateral economic and
trade relations with Vice-Premier Li Lanqing and other senior
government officials. She has also been discussing the WTO round
of negotiations and said that China and the EU will discuss the
matter this May.
</P>
<P>
Luckily for China, she added, it knows that the Dutch will
continue to criticize the EU's anti-dumping policy.
</P>
<P>
She went on to say that China and the Netherlands have agreed
to upgrade their existing bilateral cooperation agreements and
that negotiation will take place soon in the Hague.
</P>
<P>
She said that during the large Dutch trade mission's current
visit, the Netherlands and China signed a number of contracts
worth some 150 million U.S. dollars for water treatment, energy,
environmental protection, banking, insurance, and aviation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
