<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Consumer Prices Rise Slightly in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Consumer prices in the United
States edged up a modest 0.2 percent in March as falling food
costs helped to offset the biggest increase in energy prices in
more than two years, the Labor Department reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Last month's increase in the Consumer Price Index was up
slightly from 0.1 percent gains turned in for both January and
February, but still showed that inflation is remaining under
control.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, consumer inflation is rising at an annual
rate of 1.5 percent, slightly lower than the 1.6 percent price
rise recorded for all of 1998, the best performance on the
inflation front since 1986.
</P>
<P>
Economists are expecting prices will advance at a faster clip
this year as the global economy begins to recover from last year's
severe financial crisis and prices of commodities such as oil
begin to rise as demand picks up.
</P>
<P>
Energy prices jumped 1.6 percent in March. It was the first
increase since a small 0.1 percent rise last October and the
biggest one-month gain in energy prices since December 1996.
</P>
<P>
Gasoline prices rose 3.7 percent in March, their biggest rise
since August 1997. Analysts expect gasoline prices to continue
rising in the months ahead as refiners pass on the costs of a 27
percent surge in crude petroleum prices following the decision of
the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries to cut back on
production in an effort to firm up prices.
</P>
<P>
However, the big gain in energy prices last month was partially
offset by a 0.2 percent fall in food costs, the biggest one-month
drop in this category since September 1997. The price declines
were led by a 5.5 percent plunge in the vegetable prices. The
price of tomatoes dropped by 6.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The 0.2 percent rise in overall inflation was slightly below
analysts expectations. They had been looking for a 0.3 percent
jump in March because of the rapid run-up in energy costs.
</P>
<P>
Excluding the volatile energy and food categories, inflation
was well-behaved with the so-called core inflation rate rising
just 0.1 percent, matching the small increases recorded in January
and February.
</P>
<P>
Airline fares increased by 4.7 percent last month. During the
first three months of this year, airline fares jumped 41.8 percent
at an annual rate, the sharpest increase for any of the major
categories in the Consumer Price Index.
</P>
<P>
While economists believe that rising energy costs will add
probably 0.6 percentage point to overall inflation this year, they
look for inflation to remain tamed in other areas.
</P>
<P>
If that forecast is correct, it should give the Federal Reserve
the leeway to leave interest rates unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
