<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- With NATO airstrikes against Yugoslavia continuing and
military commanders seeking another dramatic increase in the
number of warplanes, the alliance's 19 foreign ministers launched
a diplomatic offensive Monday to convince Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic that he must halt military action in Kosovo
before the bombing raids cause the destruction of his country.
</P>
<P>
-- A federal judge Monday held President Bill Clinton in
contempt of court for giving "intentionally false" testimony about
his relationship with Monica S. Lewinsky in the Paula Jones
lawsuit, marking the first time that a sitting president has been
sanctioned for disobeying a court order.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- The Pentagon plans to approve the deployment of 300 more
warplanes to use against Yugoslavia, deepening American
involvement so significantly that President Clinton will almost
surely have to call up Air Force reserves, senior officials said.
</P>
<P>
-- Russian parliamentary leaders voted to delay indefinitely a
planned vote on the impeachment of President Boris Yeltsin,
stepping back from another showdown between the Kremlin and the
Parliament.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- The Clinton administration will try to sell a hostile
Congress on a WTO China pact that it doesn't yet officially back.
Meanwhile, Europe is set to start its own WTO talks with China.
</P>
<P>
-- In Jakarta, a son of Suharto was charged with corruption.
Meanwhile, the World Bank delayed 600 million U.S. dollars in
loans, fearing misuse with elections near. 
</P>
</TEXT>
