<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Suspends Cooperation With Niger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 13 (Xinhua) -- France decided to suspend its
cooperation with Niger on Tuesday after the assassination of
President Ibrahim Bare Mainassara and the coup by a group of army
officers last Friday.
</P>
<P>
"France decides to suspend immediately and until a new order (
is established) all military cooperation with the authorities of
Niamey, as well as programs of civil cooperation which do not
directly benefit the people," said French Foreign Ministry
spokeswoman Anne Gazeau-Secret.
</P>
<P>
France is Niger's biggest trade partner and aid provider.
</P>
<P>
"France reiterates with firmness its condemnation of the coup
which has cost the live of President Ibrahim Bare Mainassara and
is a step back for the democracy in Niger," said the spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
Army commander Daouda Mallam Wanke, who on Sunday succeeded the
presidency of Niger and is leading ruling Council of National
Reconciliation consisting of 14 military officers, has promised to
hand over power to a civilian government after a nine-month
interim period.
</P>
<P>
Paris provided Niger with a public development aid of 440
million francs (73 million U.S. dollars) in 1997, and sent Niamey
structural readjustment aid of 90 million francs (15 million U.S.
dollars) and 115 million francs (19 million U.S. dollars) in 1997
and 1998 respectively.
</P>
<P>
France has also helped the Niger government reach a national
pacification with the rebellious Touareg minority tribe in the
north of the country over the past several years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
