<DOCNO> XIE19990413.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Retail Sales Up 0.2 Percent in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 13 (Xinhua) -- U.S. retail sales rose 0.2
percent in March to a seasonally adjusted 239.6 billion U.S.
dollars as consumers rushed spring shopping for an early Easter
and spent big tax refunds, the Commerce Department said on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Retail sales, which represent about a third of the nation's
economic output, have kept increasing for eight months in a row,
reflecting the strong consumer demand as a result of rising
incomes and low unemployment.
</P>
<P>
The modest rise in March came on top of big sales gains of 1.3
percent in January and 1.7 percent in February, the biggest
monthly jump in five years. Both the January and February figures
were revised upward from previous estimates -- February's
substantially, from 0.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Contributing to the March rise, tax refunds were up nearly 20
percent compared to this time last year and usual holiday shopping
sprees came early, since Easter fell on April 4.
</P>
<P>
Also driving the recent stretch of robust sales: Unemployment
is near a 29-year low, stock prices as measured by the Dow Jones
average of industrial stocks have hit record highs and interest
rates are tame.
</P>
<P>
Americans' appetite for shopping is helping keep economic
growth brisk even though the country's export sales are slow
because of global economic problems that began two years ago in
Asia.
</P>
<P>
In March, sales of durable goods, items expected to last three
years or more, fell 0.2 percent, after rising a big 2.7 percent in
February. The March decline was the first since July.
</P>
<P>
Automotive sales were off 0.5 percent and sales at building
supply and hardware stores fell 0.4 percent, also after much
larger gains the month before.
</P>
<P>
Sales at furniture stores, however, continued to rise, by 0.2
percent in March. Low mortgage rates have fueled a home-buying
boom that has led to spending on new furnishings.
</P>
<P>
Excluding volatile auto sales, total retail sales were up 0.5
percent in March.
</P>
<P>
Sales of nondurable goods such as food and gasoline were up 0.6
after rising by 1 percent in February.
</P>
<P>
Sales at apparel and accessory shops jumped 1.6 percent and
rose 0.7 percent at department and general merchandise stores. At
grocery and other food stores, sales dropped 0.5 percent after a
1.5 percent increase in February, and bar and restaurant patronage
declined by 0.4 percent. Drug store sales were up 1 percent and
sales at gasoline service stations rose 1.5 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
