<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain to Send More Soldiers to Balkans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Britain is to deploy an
additional 1,800 troops to the Balkans, British Prime Minister
Tony Blair announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
That will bring the total British contingent of armed forces
in Greece and Macedonia to just over 6,300, Blair told at the
House of Commons.
</P>
<P>
The troops are to reinforce its units close to Kosovo. But a
spokesman for the British government played down any suggestion
that a ground offensive was moving closer.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said details of the planned deployment would be
announced by Blair in a statement later to the House of Commons,
which reassembled on Tuesday after its Easter break.
</P>
<P>
The extra troops will join some 4,000 British troops already in
Macedonia, originally earmarked as part of "an international force
", which is in fact formed by NATO troops only, to implement the
now largely defunct Rambouillet peace deal.
</P>
<P>
But the spokesman stressed that the move was not part of a
build-up for a land invasion of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
They would be part of a security force NATO wants to deploy in
the Serbian Province of Kosovo once the air strikes against
Yugoslavia were over and Serb forces had been withdrawn, he added.
</P>
<P>
Britain has repeatedly ruled out any possibility of invading
the province by sending ground troops to fight their way into
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"The line on this hasn't changed," the Downing Street spokesman
told a press briefing.
</P>
<P>
At the end of March, Britain had nearly 10,000 personnel in the
Balkans region, including 4,700 in Greece and Macedonia, and 4,500
peacekeepers with the NATO-led Multinational Stabilization Force (
SFOR) in Bosnia and Croatia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
