<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNSCOM Says It Can Give No Assurance of Disposal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Special
Commission (UNSCOM) said on Tuesday that it could not give the
Security Council assurances about the disposal of Iraq's
prohibited weapons programs and their possible reconstitution.
</P>
<P>
UNSCOM, in charge of dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass
destruction, said in a report that it has not received the
cooperation from Iraq necessary to conduct its work.
</P>
<P>
The report, the seventh on UNSCOM disarmament and ongoing
verification and monitoring activities, covers the period from
October 6, 1998 to April 11, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The report said it was not possible to pursue any
disarmament activities in the chemical weapons area. Iraq's
unilateral claim of August 1998, that all outstanding issues had
been resolved, was in contrast to UNSCOM's findings on the status
of verification of Iraq's declaration in its prohibited chemical
weapons activities. Iraq refused to provide documents and
evidence for the further verification.
</P>
<P>
The report said during inspections of its banned biological
weapons programs, Iraq refused to provide requested documents, and
it also hindered an inspection team sent to the country from 3 to
10 december 1998 to conduct in-depth inspections of key biological
sites.
</P>
<P>
Since December 16, when UN weapons inspectors were withdrawn
from Iraq ahead of airstrikes by the United States and the
United Kingdom, UNSCOM has carried out no work in Iraq.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990413.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France to Deploy 700 Ground Troops in Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 13 (Xinhua) -- France will deploy 700 ground
troops in Albania to carry out NATO's "Allied Harbor" operation.
</P>
<P>
French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin said on Tuesday that NATO
troops will not only be engaged in transportation and distribution
of food, but also guarding refugee camps.
</P>
<P>
"France will participate in this operation by deploying 700 men,
" he said at the National Assembly, or the lower house of
parliament.
</P>
<P>
France has already sent 58 warplanes, seven warships including
the aircraft carrier Foch, and 6,000 soldiers to participate in
the NATO operation against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Jospin also admitted that a NATO bombing killed 10 passengers
riding in a civilian train in Yugoslavia on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"We deplore the death of 10 passengers in a train during the
attack on a bridge," he said.
</P>
<P>
He described the event as a tragic but isolated incident
falling short of the rules of action of the alliance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
