<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Names Four New Federal Security Council Members </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin on
Tuesday named both chairmen of the Parliament's two chambers,
along with two other officials, as new members of the Federal
Security Council of Russia.
</P>
<P>
Federation Council Chairman Yegor Semeonovich Stroyev, State
Duma Chairman Gennady Seleznev, Presidential Office Director
Alexander Voloshin and Government Communications Bureau Director V.
P. Sherstyuk have been named members of the Federal Security
Council, a decree issued by Yeltsin said.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time that chairmen of both chambers of the
parliament were admitted into the council.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here said the move showed that President Yeltsin wants
to maintain coordination between the country's power institutions
and to stabilize the political situation prior to this year's
parliamentary election.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Security Council is Russia's highest decision-
making body under the leadership of the president. Key members of
the council include heads of the departments of power and the
Presidential Office as well as cabinet ministers. 
</P>
