<DOCNO> XIE19990413.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US, Russia Remain Apart on Kosovo Crisis Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The United States and Russia
failed to bridge differences on the ways to settle the Kosovo
crisis Tuesday, but said that they would continue to work together
for a political solution.
</P>
<P>
"The Russian position has not changed," Russian Foreign
Minister Igor Ivanov told reporters in Oslo, Norway, after a first
meeting with U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright since NATO
launched air raids against Yugoslavia three weeks ago. "The most
important thing is to keep up an active dialogue."
</P>
<P>
"We have taken a step forward, perhaps not as big a step as we
hoped, but a step forward nevertheless," Ivanov said after four
hours of talks in a hotel at Oslo airport.
</P>
<P>
Albright also said that the two countries would continue
working together for peace. She stressed that any peacekeeping
force for Kosovo must have a NATO core.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov again urged NATO to stop its air strikes so as to help
secure a peace accord. He said that the question of a peace force
was one of the most complicated issues in the talks.
</P>
<P>
Russia has been strongly opposing NATO's air campaign against
Yugoslavia and has frozen its relations with the 19-nation
military alliance. The Albright-Ivanov talks revealed the U.S.
efforts to improve ties with Russia.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the Oslo meeting, Albright' spokesman James Rubin said
Russia had a "potentially constructive role" to play in ending the
clashes in Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
