<HEADLINE> Chinese Military Leader Urges End of NATO Military Strikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- General Fu Quanyou, chief of the
General Staff of the Chinese People's Liberation Army (PLA), said
today that China urges NATO to immediately stop its military
intervention against Yugoslavia to bring the Kosovo issue back to
political settlement.
</P>
<P>
Fu, also a member of the Central Military Commission, made the
remark in a meeting with Manuel Jose Alvarenga de Sousa Santos,
chief of staff of the air force of Portugal.
</P>
<P>
Noting that NATO's wanton and indiscriminate bombing against
Yugoslavia is the concern of peace-loving countries and people in
the world, he said that the Kosovo issue, an internal affair of
Yugoslavia, should be solved by concerned parties in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
"The international community should respect sovereignty and
territorial integrity of Yugoslavia," Fu stressed.
</P>
<P>
He said that Sino-Portuguese relations have been developing
well in political, economic and other areas since the two
countries established diplomatic ties two decades ago. He added
that military-to-military relations have also developed further.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the conviction that Alvarenga's current China
visit will promote cooperation between the two countries and armed
forces.
</P>
<P>
Alvarenga said that he had a good conversation with Liu Shunyao,
commander of the PLA air force, and he gained a better
understanding of the progress the PLA air force has made in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the two air forces will maintain
high-level exchanges of visits and further increase cooperation in
education and training. 
</P>
</TEXT>
