<HEADLINE> Russia Considers to Withdraw Peace-keeping Troops From Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Russian Defense Minister Igor
Dmitriyevich Sergeyev said Tuesday that Russia was considering to
withdraw its peace-keeping troops from Bosnia in view of the
current situation in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
Sergeyev said his country is weighing all possible options,
including the withdrawal of peace-keeping troops from Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Soon after NATO began military actions against Yugoslavia on
March 24, Russia declared that its peace-keeping troops in Bosnia
have been put under the direct command of the Russian defense
minister and Anatoly Kvashnin, chief of general staff of the
Russian Armed Forces.
</P>
<P>
Sergeyev added that Russia plans to send more warships to the
Mediterranean Sea in the coming days. The warships will escort a
new floating dock to the Mediterranean Sea to replace an old one
off the Syrian coast.
</P>
<P>
The minister believed that NATO could possibly launch a ground
war against Yugoslavia. He based the assumption on the facts that
NATO's air strikes against Yugoslavia have become intensified and
the number of warplanes, taking off either from ground or sea, has
been increased. 
</P>
