<HEADLINE> No Confederation with Palestinians: Jordanian PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Prime Minister Abdel
Raouf Al-Rawabdah Tuesday ruled out any plan to establish a
confederation with the future Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
Rawabdah, who is accompanying Jordanian King Abdullah Bin
Hussein on a three-day visit to the United Arab Emirates, said
Jordan will not form a confederation with Palestine, the official
news agency WAM reported.
</P>
<P>
"Throughout the history, all confederation experiments ended up
in separation," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We, in Jordan, do not talk about a confederation. But we are
aspiring to a progressive form of unity," he added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Rawabdah indicated that a referendum will be held by
the peoples of Jordan and Palestine to determine what form the
unity between them will take after the establishment of a full and
sovereign Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat will decide later this month
whether to announce statehood on May 4, when a five-year interim
autonomy period ends according to agreements signed with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Like other countries, Jordan has been persuading Arafat to
delay the declaration until after the May 17 Israeli elections,
fearing that an early announcement could lead to the victory of
Israeli hard-line politicians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
