<DOCNO> XIE19990413.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Largest Auctioneer Handling Dunhuang Documents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Some rare documents from the
Chinese relics site Dunhuang that were lost for nearly a century
will be sold at auction next week in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The 6 items include a hand-written Buddhist scripture
translated by Xuan Zhuang, a famous monk from the Tang Dynasty (
618-907), according to Tuo Xiaotang, who is in charge of Chinese
Rare Books for China Guardian Auctions, the auctioneer.
</P>
<P>
Although these items are only a tiny part of the Dunhuang
documents that have disappeared, collectors will no doubt be
interested, he said.
</P>
<P>
In 1900, a Taoist priest, Wang Yuanlu, stumbled on a cave in
what is present-day Gansu Province that contained more than 50,000
documents and relics dating from the 4th century to the 10th.
</P>
<P>
In subsequent years, many expeditions went there to acquire the
documents and relics like Buddhist sculptures and frescoes. The
government of the Qing Dynasty (1644-1911) ordered the remaining
documents from Dunhuang to be transported to Beijing in 1907. But
after they were put in the imperial city, many were stolen.
</P>
<P>
Tuo says that the six items are some of those that were
transported to Beijing and they bear the seal of Duan Fang, a
senior dynastic official, from 1909.
</P>
<P>
Auctioneers estimate that the documents will bring as much as
50,000 yuan (6,000 U.S. dollars), but there may be a lot of
competition.
</P>
<P>
China's Cultural Relics Preservation Law prohibits such items
from leaving the country. There are as many as 50,000 of the
documents and relics in other countries. Britain alone has more
than 13,600.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Dunhuang scholars have repeatedly appealed to the
owners to return the rare documents and some patriotic businessmen
have bought Dunhuang items to return them.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990413.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
