<HEADLINE> Russia Slams NATO's Bombing of Yugoslav Train </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Ministry on
Tuesday released a statement slamming NATO's bombing of a Yugoslav
passenger train, saying the destruction of civilian targets could
not be tolerated.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the train was hit by a NATO missile on
Monday when it was crossing a bridge on its way from Leskovac.
</P>
<P>
According to Yugoslav rescue officials, 10 people were killed
and 16 injured in the attack, during which one carriage of the
train was destroyed completely.
</P>
<P>
Moscow, keeping up its strong opposition to NATO air strikes in
Yugoslavia, said in the statement that "routine NATO air strikes
on civilian objects, leading to crack down of innocent, peaceful
citizens, can only prompt deep indignation,"
</P>
<P>
"While expressing condolences to the relatives and other close
ones of the deceased, we demand a quick end to the NATO bombings
in Yugoslavia and emphasize the necessity of urgent measures to
switch to the political regulation of Kosovo."
</P>
<P>
Russia has frozen ties with NATO to express its dismay at the
bombing campaign. Russia has preferred to use diplomacy to seek
peace rather than resorting to military action. 
</P>
