<HEADLINE> Sino-German Agricultural Aid Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Today was the last day of an 11-
year Sino-German agricultural aid project in Shandong Province.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the German Ministry of Foreign Economic
Cooperation say that this was the largest and most successful of
its kind. The Germans provided aid to the people of economically
backward parts of Shandong in a project focused on solving water
shortages, halting soil erosion, water-saving irrigation, and
highway and electric power systems in villages near the Yimeng
Mountains.
</P>
<P>
The project started in 1988 in 3 counties and grew to 5 cities
and 11 counties and gave villagers access to tapwater, saving them
time in their farm work.
</P>
<P>
Per capita incomes last year were more than 1,800 yuan (217 U.S.
dollars), more than 6 times the amount when the project began.
</P>
<P>
The German government has provided 184,000 tons of wheat, 36.95
million Deutschmarks, and 684 people for consultation during the
11-year period, worth 140 million Deutschmarks, while the Chinese
have provided some capital, technicians, management staff. 
</P>
</TEXT>
