<DOCNO> XIE19990413.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Grain Market to Remain Stable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Prices for grain and edible oil
in China this year will remain stable on the whole despite small
fluctuations, according to overseas edition of Monday's People's
Daily.
</P>
<P>
Due to good harvests in consecutive years, China is abundant in
wheat stock, as the total wheat supply for 1998-1999 is expected
to hit 160 million tons, while consumption is expected at about
120 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Wheat prices are expected to rise in May as the drought that
hit China's major wheat-growing areas last winter may reduce wheat
output this year.
</P>
<P>
The nation's wheat consumption will reach 170 million tons this
year, and the price in major wheat-growing areas and sales areas
is likely to stand at 1,325 yuan per ton and 1,475 yuan per ton,
respectively, before new wheat is harvested in.
</P>
<P>
Corn price is expected to recover in later half of this year,
but only within a narrow margin, as China enjoyed a good corn
harvest in 1998. The price in major production areas and major
sale areas is projected to stand at 1,225 yuan per ton and 1,375
yuan per ton, respectively, before new corn enters the market this
year.
</P>
<P>
The nation's consumption of rice averages 120 million tons on
an annual basis and the increasing rice stocks because of
harvests in the past years will narrow the changes of price within
9 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
The prospects of edible oil market look good this year. The
price bottomed out in September last year as a result of declining
output of palm oil worldwide and China's severe crackdown on oil
smuggling.
</P>
<P>
However, the rising trend will not go far as the increasing
import of edible oil has narrowed the margin of price rise and
meanwhile, domestic market price is already higher than world
market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
