<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990413.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria's New Govt. May Face Serious Financial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The in-coming civilian government
of Olusegun Obasanjo may face serious financial problem with
Nigerian budge deficit for the first quarter of 1999 hitting 38
billion naira (about 422 million U.S. dollars), This Day newspaper
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The deficit for the first quarter of this year has surpassed
the estimated overall budget deficit of 34 billion naira for the
whole year, said the paper which obtained the figure from the
just-ended Paris meeting of donor countries sponsored by the World
Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian government's foreign reserve which stood at 7.1
billion dollars last December has now gone down to 4.2 billion
dollars, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
With the external reserve already down below the minimum
allowed and with alternative revenue generating also not
encouraging, Obasanjo may have serious financial problems unless
there is a massive injection of funds from donor agencies, the
paper pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The paper noted that the deficit of the first quarter is a very
bad omen as the situation may worsen dramatically as the in-coming
civilian government is likely to spend more money than it can
make.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted one economist as saying "the terrible thing
about the whole development is that the present administration had
hoped it would make good money from the proceeds of the
privatization exercise, but that is no longer feasible as sale of
assets is yet to begin."
</P>
<P>
Even though the crude oil prices have increased to over 12
dollars per barrel as against the nine dollars, which was used in
calculating the oil revenue for 1999, the improvement in the crude
oil prices does not help much as Nigeria must cut its oil
production in line with the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries (OPEC) directives.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian National Petroleum Corporation has reportedly
issued a statement saying that the crude oil production of the
west African country will be reduced from 2.033 million barrels
per day to 1.855 million barrels starting from May.
</P>
<P>
The external reserve position is also considered not good as it
can barely finance one month of imports as against three months
which Nigeria had maintained since 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian government promised that it would finance the
deficit for 1999 through a number of options including some
concessionary loans from the multilateral donor agencies.
</P>
<P>
However, the paper said, the Nigerian government is still
discussing with the donor agencies and none of these discussions
has been translated into concrete assistance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990413.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Reach New High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket
posted its highest close in history Tuesday, propelled by a
surprising surge on Wall Street on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The All Ordinaries Index finished 38.1 points higher Tuesday at
3,076.3, eclipsing the record of 3,060 set last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Wall Street had been expected to fall sharply Monday following
a profit warning by computer maker Compaq, but instead bullish
investors shrugged off the news and pushed the Dow Jones index to
a new high.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones index closed 165.67 points, or 1.6 percent,
higher at 10,339.51.
</P>
<P>
The All Industrials Index improved 66 points to 5,536.1, with
Australia's telecommunications major Telstra rising despite being
issued a notice by the competition regulator over local call
transfers.
</P>
<P>
Telstra was up 26 cents to 8.38 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
ANZ bank led the way for the major banks, climbing 29.8 cents
to 12.16 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Westpac bank rose 19 cents to 11.75 Australian dollars,
National Australia Bank gained 49 cents to 29.29 Australian
dollars and the Commonwealth Bank of Australia was 38.9 cents
stronger at 27.339 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The All Resources Index closed 16 points higher at 1,064.1,
with resources giant BHP gaining 34.9 cents to 14.22 Australian
dollars after Monday's news of good drilling results in the Gulf
of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
The gold index leapt 25.4 points to 1,005.2 as the bullion
price in Sydney closed at 282.6 U.S. dollars from 282.95 U.S.
dollars Monday.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 513.91 million shares traded at a value
of 746.92 million U.S. dollars, with 715 rises, 544 falls and 453
remaining steady. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990413.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 12:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Cabinet Ponders Response to Killing in S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Israel's cabinet has debated
possible retaliation after an Israeli soldier was killed by a
roadside bombing in south Lebanon Monday afternoon, Israel Radio
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a local daily revealed Tuesday that Foreign
Minister Ariel Sharon had offered Syria a deal via Moscow in
which Israel would withdraw from south Lebanon before the May
elections and open negotiations with Damascus immediately after
the elections.
</P>
<P>
Aviv Bushinsky, spokesman for Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu, said the cabinet held an emergency session Monday
night to discuss the government's strategy in Lebanon, including
what retaliatory action to take.
</P>
<P>
The ministers met several hours after 21-year-old Noam Barnea
was killed by a roadside bomb while patrolling the security zone
in south Lebanon. Hezbollah guerrillas have claimed
responsibility for the bombing.
</P>
<P>
The killing of Barnea brought to eight the number of the
Israelis who have lost their lives in the security zone since
the beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
The other seven, including a brigadier-general, were killed in
two attacks in less than a week in late February, which triggered
a large-scale retaliatory air raids on Lebanon by the Israeli
army.
</P>
<P>
The local daily Haaretz quoted security sources as saying that
similar action will be possibly taken this time.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli army said the latest bombing occurred not far from
the village of Arnoun just outside the security zone, marking the
third time within a month that Hezbollah guerrillas have used the
village to stage attacks.
</P>
<P>
Israel has warned of harsh response if Hezbollah guerrillas
continued to attack Israeli military targets in the security zone
from civilian villages.
</P>
<P>
A ceasefire understanding brokered by the United States after
a major Israeli offensive against Lebanon in 1996 bans the
warring sides from attacking on or from civilian villages.
</P>
<P>
Briefing the defense committee of the parliament Monday,
before the bombing in the security zone, Defense Minister Moshe
Arens said Syria must rein in Hezbollah activities, saying
"nothing happens there without their approval."
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah guerrillas are fighting to end Israel's occupation
of the security zone it carved out in 1985 with a claimed aim of
protecting its northern areas.
</P>
<P>
Syria, the main power-broker in Lebanon, has rejected an
Israeli proposal that Israel pull out its troops out of the
security zone on condition that the Lebanese government make
necessary security arrangements.
</P>
<P>
Damascus has insisted that any solution to the Lebanese issue
must be a broad accord which will also guarantee the return of
its Golan Heights seized by Israel in the 1967 war.
</P>
<P>
Haaretz said that Sharon, who is on a visit to Russia, has
asked Moscow to serve as the intermediary between Israel and
Syria in a deal in which Israel would pull out from Lebanon first
and open talks with Syria later.
</P>
<P>
According to the Sharon proposal, Israel would complete the
withdrawal from south Lebanon before the May 17 elections. During
this period, Damascus has to prevent any cross-border attacks on
Israel by Hezbollah or other groups.
</P>
<P>
Then, if Netanyahu is re-elected, the Israeli government would
immediately begin negotiations with Syria over the Golan Heights
and a peace agreement between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
But the proposal, partly aimed at boosting Netanyahu's chance
of re-election, did not mention to what extent Israel is willing
to make concessions on the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that Syria would reject the proposal. Damascus
has insisted that Israel should have to promise a complete
withdrawal from Golan before any negotiations are resumed.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Syrian talks broke off in early 1996. Since coming
to power in june that year, Netanyahu has pledged that he would
never give up the Golan Heights because of its "vital strategic
significance" to Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990413.0126 </DOCNO>
