<DOCNO> XIE19990413.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 12:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Denies Offering Syria Deal on Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu and Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon Tuesday strongly
denied offering deal to Syria on peace talks and troops withdrawal
from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The denial is in response to an article in local daily Haaretz's
Tuesday edition, which said that Sharon, who is in Moscow on a
two-day visit, had asked Russia to pass on his two-part proposal
to Syria.
</P>
<P>
In the proposal, Israel offers to complete the withdrawal from
south Lebanon before the May 17 elections and in return, Damascus
has to prevent any cross-border attacks on Israel by Hezbollah or
other groups in the meantime.
</P>
<P>
Then, if Netanyahu is re-elected, the Israeli government will
immediately begin negotiations with Syria over the Golan Heights
and a peace agreement between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Israel seized the Golan Heights from Syria in the 1967 Middle
East war and Syria has vowed not to resume the peace talks, which
have been stalled since 1996, with Israel unless it agrees to
return the strategic plateau.
</P>
<P>
Aviv Bushinsky, Netanyahu's spokesman, said the report was
"another incorrect story by the newspaper."
</P>
<P>
Sharon told Israel Radio from Moscow that the report is "a
lie," saying he had not discussed the Lebanon issue with Russian
officials.
</P>
<P>
Under mounting public pressure sparked by rising Israeli
casualties in south Lebanon, the Israeli government has been
seeking ways out of the conflict in the security zone, set up by
Israel in 1985 with a claimed aim of protecting its north from
Lebanese guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and its main power-broker Syria have rejected an
Israeli offer last year, which conditioned the troops pullout on
Beirut's security guarantee for its north.
</P>
<P>
Syria wants to clinch a broader deal with Israel, in which
Israel will agree to relinquish the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
The paper said the Sharon proposal, partly aimed at boosting
Netanyahu's chance of re-election, did not mention to what extent
Israel is willing to make concessions on the Golan.
</P>
<P>
It also said that Syria is expected to reject the proposal
since Damascus has insisted that Israel promise a complete
withdrawal from Golan before any negotiations are resumed.
</P>
<P>
Since coming to power in 1996, Netanyahu has pledged that he
would never give up the Golan Heights because of its "vital
strategic significance" to Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
