<HEADLINE> Chinese Leader Ends Visit to Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Li Peng, chairman of the Standing
Committee of the National People's Congress of China, left here
for Thailand on Tuesday afternoon at the end of a two-day official
goodwill visit to Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
During his stay here, Li held talks with Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina on bilateral relations and regional and world issues of
mutual concern and the two sides agreed to make efforts to further
the existing friendly relations of cooperation between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed that as China and Bangladesh are both
developing countries in Asia, it conforms with the long-term and
fundamental interest of both countries to develop lasting friendly
relations of good-neighborliness between them.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese leader called on President Shahabuddin Ahmed and
met with Foreign Minister Abdus Samad Azad on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Li jointly unveiled the foundation stone of the
Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman International Conference Center
with Hasina. The conference center, to be built with financial and
technical assistance from China, is expected to be the main venue
of the 13th summit of the Non-Alignment Movement scheduled for the
year 2001 in the Bangladeshi capital of Dhaka.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh is the fifth leg of Li's six-nation tour across
Europe and Asia, which had already taken him to Greece, Turkey,
Syria and Pakistan before Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
Li last visited this South Asian nation in 1989 as premier.
</P>
</TEXT>
