<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-Dutch Seminar on Water Control Begins in Beijing (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chinese Vice Premier Wen Jiabao told the opening ceremony that
China pays great attention to water conservancy works and has made
great progress in this regard over the past several decades.
</P>
<P>
He said that due to China's special natural and geographical
conditions, the rapid expansion of its economy and the growth of
its population, water conservancy problems are becoming
increasingly acute.
</P>
<P>
"Disastrous flooding, a shortage of water resources, and the
deterioration of the ecological environment have become the three
leading problems relating to water that have restricted the
sustained growth of China's economy and other aspects of the
society," Wen said.
</P>
<P>
The vice premier said the disastrous flooding in China last
year has brought the entire nation to a consensus that more
investment must be made in water conservancy projects.
</P>
<P>
He said that China can learn from the Netherlands with its
advanced technology and rich experience in flood control and the
protection of a water environment. The two countries have
conducted effective cooperation in river dredging, the protection
of the water environment, and water management, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The two sides signed a "Memorandum of Understanding on
Integrated Water and River Basin Management" on Tuesday following
the opening ceremony. 
</P>
