<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Says Regional Crisis Get Members Closer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The Asian regional economic
crisis has helped the member nations of the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) to get closer together, ASEAN
Secretary-General Rodolfo Severino said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Severino told journalists at the start of a four-day Australian
visit that the nine ASEAN members had got closer together on
security issues and financial regulation during the course of the
regional crisis.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said Australia's involvement as an ASEAN dialogue
partner was crucial, "we in ASEAN feel that Australia has a
critical role to play, not only in the economic prosperity of
Southeast Asia, but also in the stability and the peace of the
region."
</P>
<P>
"And so we look to the collaboration of Australia in these
endeavors of recovery and social protection, and also in examining
the ways by which we can straighten out the deficiencies in our
corporate and financial sectors."
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Thailand, Indonesia, the Philippines, Brunei,
Malaysia, Vietnam, Singapore, Laos and Myanmar, while Cambodia is
a prospective member.
</P>
<P>
Severino admitted that ASEAN's prestige as the region's leading
multilateral forum had been severely dented by the Asian meltdown.
</P>
<P>
But he said far from being the harbinger of ASEAN's
disintegration, the turmoil has in fact helped bring the member
nations closer together.
</P>
<P>
"The opposite has happened, and instead of ASEAN being in
disarray, the crisis has impelled ASEAN to come together closer
and strengthen its cooperation and its integration," Severino
said.
</P>
<P>
It has also accelerated the formation of a South East Asian
free-trade area and boosted the possibility of a single regional
currency, he said.
</P>
<P>
Severino said he also hoped the prickly issue of independence
for East Timor would also be sorted out soon, either through
domestic efforts, or via U.N.-sponsored talks between Indonesia
and the troubled province's former colonial master, Portugal.
</P>
<P>
"All I can say is that we wish all of these efforts well, so
that violence is reduced or eliminated," Severino said.
</P>
<P>
The island has been wracked by violence over recent months, and
Indonesia's new President B. J. Habibie has promised the East
Timorese will be able to decide in a ballot later this year if
they want more autonomy from Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
Severino will be holding talks with Deputy Prime Minister and
Trade Minister Tim Fischer and Foreign Minister Alexander Downer
and senior Australian officials during his visit.
</P>
<P>
He will also be key-note speaker at a meeting here of the
Pacific Economic Cooperation Council, or PECC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
