<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Official Expresses Confidence in HK's Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Derek Fatchett, visiting
British minister of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs,
said here Tuesday that British confidence in Hong Kong remains
high.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a luncheon hosted by the Foreign Correspondents'
Club, Fatchett said it is the welcoming evidence that China
remains committed to giving Hong Kong the high degree of autonomy
promised in the Joint Declaration and to preserving Hong Kong's
special characteristics.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the qualitative improvements in Sino-British
relations would not have been possible without the successful
handover of Hong Kong; or the successful implementation of "one
country, two systems".
</P>
<P>
On the special characteristics that Hong Kong continues to
preserve after the handover, he said freedom of expression is
alive and well in Hong Kong. So is pluralism.
</P>
<P>
Noting a number of difficult tests, not least in the economic
field that the government of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (SAR) has faced since the handover, Fatchett said he was
confident that Hong Kong would move on from recession and the
shock waves of the financial crisis, well positioned as a more
competitive force within the region.
</P>
<P>
Fundamentals remain stronger here than in many parts of the
world, he said.
</P>
<P>
Fatchett said British interests and confidence in Hong Kong
remain high, adding: "We respect the autonomy of the SAR;
interfering is not on our agenda." "Our interest in Hong Kong,
one of our major partners in Asia, extends across the spectrum."
</P>
<P>
He noted that Britain is the largest foreign investor in Hong
Kong, with more than 1,000 British companies based here.
</P>
<P>
Its share in all foreign investment in manufacturing and
services in Hong Kong amounts to around 27 percent. "We receive 80
percent of Hong Kong's steadily growing investment in Europe", he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said international confidence not just measured by
statistics, but also by intangible factors such as belief in the
rule of law, the integrity and independence of the judiciary.
</P>
<P>
"We welcome the fact that the Hong Kong SAR government has
restated its commitment to upholding the rule of law as an
imperative and a duty", he added.
</P>
<P>
Fatchett arrived here Monday on his first visit to Hong Kong
since it returned to China on July 1, 1997. Tung Chee Hwa, chief
executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region, met with
him on that day.
</P>
<P>
He spoke on environment and business at a breakfast hosted by
the British Chamber of Commerce in Hong Kong Tuesday and this was
followed by a press conference.
</P>
<P>
He is scheduled to leave here for Beijing Tuesday evening.
</P>
</TEXT>
