<HEADLINE> Mozambican PM Defends Nationalization Achievements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican Prime Minister Pascoal
Mocumbi has called upon his countrymen to value and preserve the
achievements of nationalization since independence of the southern
African country.
</P>
<P>
Mocumbi made the call in response to questions of some members
of parliament Monday.
</P>
<P>
The legislators from the largest opposition party, the
Mozambican National Resistance (RENAMO), had reportedly demanded
that the private properties including real estate nationalized in
the early period after independence be returned to their original
owners.
</P>
<P>
In his previous speeches, Mocumbi noted that in late 1980s the
government had corrected some slips made in the nationalization,
but he stressed that those nationalized in line with the laws
would not be privatized.
</P>
<P>
The Mozambican people should value and preserve what they have
achieved, especially in such fields as education, health and
housing, Tuesday's Noticias newspaper quoted the prime minister as
saying.
</P>
<P>
"Despite differences in political belief, it is our common
responsibility to maintain fast economic growth and to constantly
increase people's incomes and solving the structural problems in
Mozambique," he said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that his government was happy that it had
strengthened social peace and economic stability and brought
perceptible benefits to the people, which has won acknowledge and
appreciation from the international community.
</P>
<P>
However, the prime minister admitted that there is a lot to do
in the management of the state and the national development.
</P>
</TEXT>
