<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Youth Lack Creativity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- A recent survey of 12,000 middle
school and university students in China revealed that Chinese
youth still lack creativity.
</P>
<P>
The survey, the first of its kind in China and jointly
conducted by the Ministry of Education, the Chinese Communist
Youth League Central Committee, and the China Association for
Science and Technology, found that most of the youngsters have
little knowledge of the structure and functions of the brain.
</P>
<P>
Ma Kangmei, one of the experts conducting the survey, said that
only 4.7 percent of the respondents have strong self-confidence,
curiosity and determination, and are likely to raise questions,
all qualities associated with creativity.
</P>
<P>
The survey also showed that only 14.9 percent of the youngsters
have great imaginations and the ability to probe into questions
and gather information.
</P>
<P>
Although 68 percent of the respondents agreed that intellectual
competitions are helpful to increasing the ability to observe,
analyze, and solve problems, only 33 percent of them had ever
participated in such activities.
</P>
<P>
Ma said most Chinese youth are affected by stereotypical
thought, and are likely to blindly respect authority. And this
tendency grows stronger with age.
</P>
<P>
However, experts say that youthful creativity has no
connection with gender, and that this traditional concept hinders
the full development of female creativity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
