<HEADLINE> Roundup: Dutch Queen's Visit to Boost Trade Ties with China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chinese light industrial products, cereals and oils, food,
livestock products, garments, textiles and toys can be seen
everywhere in the Netherlands, through which those products are
often shipped to other European countries.
</P>
<P>
Dutch products such as Shell lubricating oil, Philips household
electrical appliances, Lux soap and Wall's ice-cream are well-
known and welcomed by the Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
The Netherlands is also the fourth largest European investor in
China. Almost all of the renowned Dutch companies have established
enterprises or offices in China, and Dutch capital flowing to
China has kept at a double-digit growth rate since 1994.
</P>
<P>
By last February, Dutch contractual investment in China
totaled 3.467 billion U.S. dollars, serving the electrical,
telecommunications, household electrical appliances and chemical
sectors of China's coastal regions.
</P>
<P>
Dutch Prime Minister Wim Kok during his visit to China in 1995
agreed to extend to China some 1.25 billion Dutch guilders in
mixed government loans, and one-half-billion Dutch guilders in
commercial loans at low interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the two countries have conducted fruitful cooperation
in technology. By the end of last year, the two sides had signed a
total of 268 contracts involving 551 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Sources say the two countries are expected to increase
cooperation in the areas of petrochemicals, shipping, and
electronics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
