<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Reshuffle Cabinet Next Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan President Chandrika
Kumaratunga will reshuffle her cabinet early next week to pave the
way for some ministers to take up new posts following her ruling
party's victory in last week's provincial polls.
</P>
<P>
Environment Minister Nandimitra Ekanayake, Minister for Social
Services Berty Premalal Dissanayake and two deputy ministers are
expected to take over as chief ministers in the four provinces of
Central, North Central, Uva and Sabaragamuwa, officials said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Susil Premajayanth will continue to be the chief minister of
Western Province.
</P>
<P>
They will take oaths as chief ministers immediately after the
lists of names of the newly elected members of the Provincial
Councils were declared by a gazette notification on April 15, a
senior government spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The ruling People's Alliance swept the five provincial councils
in elections last Tuesday, beating the main opposition United
National Party by a narrow margin.
</P>
<P>
It was not immediately clear who will be brought in by
Kumaratunga in the reshuffle that may be the last before
parliamentary and presidential elections due next year.
</P>
<P>
President Kumaratunga last reshuffled her cabinet in June 1997.
</P>
