<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela Calls for Closer Ties with China, Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 13 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Neslon Mandela said Tuesday that increasing trade and investment
between South Africa, China and Russia was of great importance
within a framework which promoted development,joint ventures and a
more equal balance in trade.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a business breakfast in Midrand, a city between
Johannesburg and Pretoria, Mandela said economic relations with
the two countries were important to improve the lives of millions
of South Africans.
</P>
<P>
South Africa regarded China and Russia as important partners
for cooperation in the multilateral arena, he said.
</P>
<P>
"They can help reorient the international and multilateral
institutions that regulate the world's political, social and
economic systems, so that they better serve the needs of
development and better reflect the democratic ideals of our age...
so that they support, rather than hinder the rebirth of Africa."
</P>
<P>
Mandela made the remarks ahead of his visit to China and Russia
due to start from late April. In addition to China and Russia,
Mandela will also visit Hungary and Pakistan, Mandela's office
told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Mandela is expected to arrive in Russia on April 27 on the
first leg of a four-nation offical trip, diplomatic sources said.
</P>
<P>
China and Russia were among the last few countries that Mandela
would bid farewell to before retiring after the June 2 general
elections.
</P>
<P>
Thabo Mbeki, chairman of the ruling African National Congress,
and current deputy state president, will become top leader of
South Africa after the election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
