<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Minister Vows to Care for Elderly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government will give
special attention to policies and laws that relate to the aged, a
Kenyan cabinet minister has said.
</P>
<P>
Home Affairs, National Heritage, Culture and Social Service
Minister Shariff Nassir said Monday that the new policies,
contained in the 16-year poverty eradication plan released last
month, will address income security, health care and public
education of the aged.
</P>
<P>
Senior citizens have a right to basic needs, the Daily Nation
newspaper Tuesday quoted the minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
Opening a six-day African Regional Workshop on Aging, Nassir
said that they should be enabled to "live in dignity and security,
have access to cultural, spiritual and recreational resources and
be free from physical and mental abuse."
</P>
<P>
He said issues related to the poor and the old should be
addressed from the grassroots as they also determine the level of
democracy and good governance in a country.
</P>
<P>
"Africa has for long been engaged in wars and killing, and we
don't have enough time to think about our aged," Nassir added.
</P>
<P>
The workshop, organized by the African Gerontological Society,
was attended by delegates from more than 10 African countries.
The World Health Organization's aging and health chief Alex
Kalache also participated in the workshop. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
