<HEADLINE> No Conditions for Release of Hostages: President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine President Joseph
Estrada rejected Tuesday the request of the National Democratic
Front (NDF) to free a female guerrilla and 50 political detainees
following the release earlier by the rebels of a military sergeant
and a police officer it had kept hostage.
</P>
<P>
In a radio interview this morning, the president said the
government never made any such deal with the NDF for the release
of the government hostages.
</P>
<P>
"We never had such a deal. We only said that we will give the
NDF until Monday, April 19, to release all the hostages. But we
never struck any deal about the release of the female guerrillas
and the detainees," he said.
</P>
<P>
The NDF had released Police Chief Inspector Roberto Bernal and
Sgt. Alipio Lozada as part of its commitment to release all
government hostages it had kidnapped.
</P>
<P>
It has committed to release the remaining hostages - Brig. Gen.
Victor Obillo, Capt. Eduardo Montealto and another military
officer on or before April 19.
</P>
<P>
In a separate radio interview, Presidential Spokesman Jerry
Barican said the government is standing pat on its position to
seek the unconditional release of these remaining hostages.
</P>
<P>
According to reports, the NDF has asked the government to show
its "goodwill" by releasing 17-year old Jelyn Dayong and 50
political detainees.
</P>
<P>
Government troops captured Dayong during an encounter with
rebels in Mindanao last month, and turned her over to the
Department of Social Welfare and Development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
