<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bingling Temple Grottoes Restored After Renovation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The Bingling Temple Grottoes in
northwest China's Gansu Province which were seriously damaged by
seepage over the past three decades have been restored after a one-
year reinforcement project costing 4.5 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
The 1,600-year-old grottoes are located at the upper reaches of
the Liujiaxia reservoir and have been listed under State-level
protection.
</P>
<P>
On a precipice about 100-meters long, there are more than 800
clay Buddhist and Tibetan sculptures and frescos covering an area
of 900 square meters.
</P>
<P>
The sculptures, frescos, and caves were damaged by seepage that
began at the time the reservoir was completed.
</P>
<P>
The renovation project was undertaken by the northwest branch
of the Scientific Research Institute of the Ministry of Railways
beginning in September of 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
