<HEADLINE> China Regrets Over NATO Bombing of Yugoslavian Train </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua)-- China today expressed its deep
regret over NATO's bombing of a Yugoslavian passenger train, which
has resulted in injuries and loss of lives.
</P>
<P>
China strongly demands once again that NATO immediately halt
its air strike against Yugoslavia so as to wipe out the
humanitarian disaster there, Chinese foreign ministry spokesman
Sun Yuxi said at a routine press conference here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
In response to a question concerning China's entry to the WTO,
the spokesman said during Premier Zhu Rongji's current visit to
the U.S., the U.S. side has committed to supporting China's entry
into the organization in 1999. Relevant departments of both
countries will continue to work in this regard, and try to achieve
this goal as set forth in the statement signed by Premier Zhu and
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
When asked about the question related to illegal border
crossing and immigration, Sun said the Chinese Government has
always opposed such activities, and has taken a series of measures
to prevent illegal exits and combat illegal immigration. China is
willing to work together with relevant countries to stop such
activities, he added.  
