<HEADLINE> Kenya to Create Road Board to Speed up Road </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Ministry of Public Works
and Housing has submitted a bill to the Parliament on setting up
a Kenya Road Board to promote the rehabilitation of the decrepit
road networks in the east African country.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a meeting attended by senior officials Monday, head
of the Ministry Katana Ngala said the board would administer road
maintenance, rehabilitation and development which is designated
road agencies.
</P>
<P>
According to the East African Standard newspaper report
Tuesday, the minister said the board will mainly composed by
members from the private sector and organizations.
</P>
<P>
He noted that evaluation delivery of works of the road agencies
will be through technical, financial and permanence audits and
the board will advise him accordingly.
</P>
<P>
Ngala also pointed out that corruption had dented his
ministry's image, raised concern among Kenyans and donors, saying
that corrective measures must be taken to reverse the situation.
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper Kenya Times Monday carried a headlined story
"1.2 billion shillings (about 200 million U.S. dollars) rip-off
in road scam".
</P>
<P>
Ngala said,"there is a lot of collusion between contractors,
the officers and consultants and this must stop."
</P>
<P>
Mohammed Isahakia, Permanent Secretary of the ministry, told
the participants that the draft bill for the Kenya Roads Board
containing comments from Attorney-General Amos Wake would also be
tabled the parliament soon. 
</P>
