<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation of E. African States Under Control: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 13 (Xinhua) -- All members of the East
African Cooperation (EAC), Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda, have
succeeded in bringing inflation under control after carrying out
prudent fiscal and monetary policies.
</P>
<P>
A report on the macro-economic performance in east Africa for
1997/98 said that the inflation rates in the three countries have
fallen to a single digit level.
</P>
<P>
According to the report released at the EAC Monetary Affairs
Committee meeting in Tanzania's northern of Arusha Monday,
inflation in Kenya dropped to 2.3 percent in March this year from
12.3 percent in the same period last year, while Uganda's
underlying inflation was 2.3 percent by the end of last June.
</P>
<P>
In Tanzania, underlying inflation declined to 9.6 percent in
1998, the Daily News Tuesday quoted the report as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, the report noted that real gross domestic product
(GDP) decelerated and remained below target largely because of the
El Nino weather phenomenon which adversely affected the
performance of the agricultural sector.
</P>
<P>
The slowdown of Kenya's GDP growth to 4.8 percent was
attributed to fall in investments, insecurity and bad weather,
whereas Uganda's GDP increased by 5.5 percent due to strong
recovery in food production.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania's GDP growth fell to 3.3 percent in 1998 from 3.5
percent in the previous year due to the El Nino-charged heavy
floods which resulted in the reduction of agricultural production.
 Agriculture accounted for more than 50 percent of Tanzania's GDP.
</P>
<P>
The report said that Kenya's challenge is to improve its
economic growth to attain the targeted goal of seven percent by
next year. Tanzania is faced with an uphill task, while Uganda is
on the right track to reach the target if current economic
strategies are well implemented.
</P>
<P>
The report also observed that the currencies of the three
states depreciated last year in line with the developments in the
current accounts and there was a general decline in the treasury
bill interest rates. The treasury bill rates were reflected in
the deposit and lending rates which remained high.
</P>
<P>
But the report has recommended that the current monetary policy
stance in the three countries should be maintained and even
strengthened. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
