<DOCNO> XIE19990413.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Judges Forms Self-disciplinary Body </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan judges have set up a
committee to oversee the corruption within the judiciary in a bid
to improve judicial services in the east African country.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Chief Justice Zacchaeus Chesoni said Monday that the
creation of the committee, which aimed at supervising the
implementation of a report worked out two years ago by the Kwach
Committee which was named after one appeal judge.
</P>
<P>
The Kwach Committee's proposals included the monitoring of
judges' output and performance, opening 24-hour tourist courts at
Kenya's two biggest airports in Mombasa and Nairobi, and the
splitting up of the High Court in criminal and civil and family
divisions.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Nation newspaper Tuesday quoted Chesoni as saying
that the newly-formed judges committee to be headed by Appeal
Judge Evans Gicheru will supervise the transfers of magistrates
and put pressure on judges and magistrates with pending judgements
in their dockets,
</P>
<P>
Addressing a meeting of Appeal and High Courts judges, Chesoni
said the fact that some judicial staff had been charged
demonstrated that some of the recommendations by the Kwach
Committee report were being implemented.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that corruption should be fought not merely because
it is a condition for continued flow of foreign aids but because
it is enemy of democracy and good governance.
</P>
<P>
"Corruption like AIDS can wipe out a whole nation, " he said.
"The judiciary is ready to chart the way forward, hoping that the
executive and legislative branches will follow."
</P>
<P>
Corruption could not be checked if strategies stopped at the
level of rhetoric, the chief justice added.
</P>
<P>
The international financial institutions and Western donors
have been reluctant to give assistance to Kenya just because of
serious corruption in the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
