<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Govt. Owes $282M to Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Zambian government owes an all
time high 649.3 billion kwacha (some 282 million U.S. dollars) to
the central bank and other commercial banks by March 19, the
latest statistics from the Bank of Zambia showed.
</P>
<P>
The increase of the government debt represents a rise of nine
percent from the 593.3 billion kwacha (about 258 million dollars)
registered at the end of the fortnight ending on March 5, the
statistics from the central bank indicated.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the Zambian government's debt with the banking
system was about 563 billion kwacha (about 245 million dollars) by
December 1998, the Financial Mail newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The increasing banking system claims on the government implies
continued reliance by the government on its borrowing from the
commercial banks and the central bank to meet its short term
financing requirements, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The government borrowing from the commercial banks and central
bank is done through the issuance of treasury bills and bonds.
</P>
<P>
The business community is concerned with increased government
borrowing from the banking system because this is leaving less
credit for the private sector to invest in expansion program and
capital equipment while also pushing up interest rates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990413.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Write Off Mozambique's Debt: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 13 (Xinhua) -- South Africa would announce
the scrapping of Mozambique's debt within days, South African
Finance Minister Trevor Manuel said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Business Day newspaper Tuesday quoted Manuel as saying that
an announcement of the debt forgiveness was only a matter of
formality.
</P>
<P>
Although there was no official confirmation from Maputo, South
African government sources said Mozambique owed the South African
government about 40 million rand (6.45 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
This excluded loans by South African parastatals such as
electricity supplier Eskom, according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
It was not clear whether the gesture would include funds owned
to South African state-owned companies.
</P>
<P>
Manuel, who has been a key proponent of the debt relief
initiative for the world's poorest nations, said that South Africa
would continue to take the lead in pushing for debt relief in the
international arena.
</P>
<P>
South Africa has already written off about one billion rand
(160 million dollars) owed by Namibia since its independence from
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique, which has an external debt estimated at more than
five billion dollars, is one of the first African beneficiaries of
the international debt relief program supported by the World Bank,
the International Monetary Fund and the African Development Bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
