<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam, EU Begin Talks on Trade, Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam and European Union (EU)
began investment and trade talks here Tuesday that are hoped will
clear long-standing obstacles in trade and investment.
</P>
<P>
A Trade Ministry official, who will join the negotiations, told
the Saigon Times Daily that the meeting, which will last until
Thursday, would center on difficulties encountered by both sides.
</P>
<P>
The difficulty for Vietnam in selling to the EU focuses on
three main points. The first is that garment quotas into the EU
for Vietnam, although notably enlarged, have yet to match
Vietnam's garment capacity and potentiality. Vietnam is seeking
even more quotas.
</P>
<P>
The second involves Vietnamese footwear exports to the EU.
These items require Vietnam's certificates of origin, but the
certificates have recently been faked, thus damaging the prestige
of Vietnamese products. Several EU traders have proposed
decreasing footwear imports from Vietnam, and the two sides will
discuss ways to resolve the counterfeit problem.
</P>
<P>
The third is that Vietnam is still in the No.2 List of
fisheries export countries into the EU. Despite the EU having
recognized 33 Vietnamese seafood processors, it has yet to
transfer these firms to No.1 List, which provides several tax
privileges.
</P>
<P>
The EU also has three main difficulties trading with Vietnam to
be discussed at the meeting. First is Vietnam's import duties on
wines and spirits, which now stand at between 60-100 percent.
These levels are too high for EU companies while most of the wine
consumed in Vietnam comes from the EU.
</P>
<P>
Next the union says Vietnam's current minimum prices for import
duty calfficiates here.
</P>
<P>
According to the Saigon Times Daily, the two sides were
expected to reach a decision soon, as the opportunity to penetrate
the EU by Vietnamese companies would be killed off if by 2001 the
transfer was not endorsed. Results of the talks will have to be
submitted to the Vietnamese Government and a higher EU body for
any final decisions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
