<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 07:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former PM Muzzles His Media Against Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon's former Prime Minister
Rafik Hariri has ordered his media to refrain from airing
political programs and news commentaries, and to restrict their
local reporting to non-controversial issues.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Star said Tuesday that Hariri's decision followed
mounting criticism from the cabinet that the Future TV and Radio
Orient owned by him had turned into a tool for the opposition to
discredit the incumbent government.
</P>
<P>
As of Saturday night, the main news on Future TV and Radio
Orient focused on the crises in Kosovo and Iraq. Local news was
restricted to straightforward reporting on meetings or visits by
the country's top officials.
</P>
<P>
According to sources close to Hariri, the former premier was
not asking for "political favors" in return for the decision to
muzzle what the current Prime Minister Salim Hoss perceived as an
anti-government campaign.
</P>
<P>
"In the higher interest of the country, Hariri has decided
that it was best to defuse the political climate amid the public
debate over the 1999 budget bill," one source said.
</P>
<P>
The source strongly denied speculation that Hariri was
demanding that some corruption files implicating him or political
allies in the misuse or squandering of public funds be closed.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the cabinet transferred a report on
suspected financial scandals by Hariri and his three ministers to
the state prosecutor's office for investigation.
</P>
<P>
The construction tycoon, who made most of his fortunes in
Saudi Arabia, came to power in 1992 after the end of the
country's 1975-1990 civil war.
</P>
<P>
He was replaced by his long-time rival Hoss after Emile Lahoud
was elected the country's new president last November. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
