<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Egyptian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading Egyptian newspapers on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Al-Ahram:
</P>
<P>
-- Expressing deep concern over the stalled Middle East peace
process on all tracks, Egypt and Japan stressed the need for
cooperation between the two countries to help achieve a just,
lasting and comprehensive peace in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, who is in Japan on a visit,
and Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi expressed the desires in
a joint statement issued at the end of their talks Monday.
</P>
<P>
Al-Akhbar:
</P>
<P>
-- Egypt is attaching great importance to the
Euro-Mediterranean foreign ministerial conference, which is to be
hosted by the German city of Stuttgart on April 15-16.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa will attend the meeting,
which will discuss means to activate Euro-Mediterranean
partnership in political, economic, and cultural domains.
</P>
<P>
Al-Gomhuria:
</P>
<P>
-- The conference on water and decertification in Arab
countries is to start Saturday in Cairo to discuss a document on
water developing in Egypt and the Arab world as a whole.
</P>
<P>
The document incorporates 20 recommendations to solve the
problem of water shortage.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian Gazette:
</P>
<P>
-- The World Bank spoke highly of the economic reforms adopted
by Egypt and the fruitful achievements including the higher growth
rate, national income, exports and more jobs.
</P>
<P>
According to a report on northern African and Middle East
economies, the World Bank said Egypt is expected to cross the new
century with better potentials than expected in the field of
economic prosperity and improved standard of living.
</P>
<P>
The report also hailed Morocco, Tunisia and some regional
countries for their economic achievements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
