<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Concerned About Violence in East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, April 13 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Minister of
Foreign Affairs and Trade Don McKinnon Tuesday called on the
Indonesian Government to investigate the violence in East Timor
during Easter.
</P>
<P>
"Although there are conflicting reports about the number of
East Timorese killed in Liquica during Easter, it's clear there
was an attack by anti-independence militia groups. This incident
must be investigated properly and the perpetrators brought to
justice," McKinnon told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"I've already instructed our Ambassador in Jakarta to take this
up with the Indonesian Government and military," he added.
</P>
<P>
Violence by any group in East Timor can not be condoned,
particularly in the leadup to the vote on autonomy in July, he
said, adding people should not be intimidated by violence or
threats.
</P>
<P>
The New Zealand Minister urged the Indonesian Government and
military to work to disarm groups.
</P>
<P>
"It is vital both pro and anti independence groups lay down
their arms," he said.
</P>
<P>
McKinnon said his country remains supportive of the United
Nations efforts to settle the East Timor dispute. He reaffirmed
New Zealand's willingness to contribute to a U.N. presence in the
territory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
