<HEADLINE> AAA041334 COMESA Internal Tariffs Reduced by </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The Common Market for
Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) member states have so far
reduced their internal tariffs by 60 -90 percent, a senior COMESA
official said.
</P>
<P>
COMESA's Director of Trade, Customs and Monetary Issues
Division, Charles Chanthunya told a COMESA meeting held here
Monday the regional organization is optimistic that a free trade
area will be in force by October next year according to a
schedule.
</P>
<P>
"COMESA is surely geared for a Free Trade Area in October next
year," Chanthunya noted.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Mail Tuesday quoted him as telling delegates to a
third Automated System for Customs Data and Management user group
meeting that Madagascar and Egypt have reduced tariff rates on
products from fellow members by 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
Chanthunya said that Kenya, Tanzania, Mauritius, the Sudan,
Uganda and Zimbabwe have reduced tariff rates by 80 percent,
Malawi by 70 percent while Rwanda, Burundi and Zambia by 60
percent.
</P>
<P>
He also pointed out that in order to operate as a trading bloc
at the world market, COMESA members need to have accurate external
trade statistics and promote their investment potentials through
most modern data processing and storage facility.
</P>
<P>
The World Trade Organization (WTO) encourages international
trade to be conducted through electronic commerce and computer
networking.
</P>
<P>
There are 77 countries worldwide currently operating the
Automated System for Customs Data and Management which was
tailored by the United Nations Conference on Trade And Development
and funded by the European Union. 
</P>
