<HEADLINE> Beijing Court Takes Lead in Addressing Enforcement Difficulties  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The reform measure taken by the Chaoyang District People's
Court involves enforcement procedures that are typically
undertaken by the director and staff of the court's Enforcement
Division, according to the Beijing-based China Daily today.
</P>
<P>
Besides hearing cases, Chinese courts are accountable for
enforcing their judgments -- sometimes in the face of active
enforcement -- through law enforcement divisions established since
the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
The new approach adopted by the Chaoyang court is intended to
speed up the handling of a backlog of judgments that await
enforcement, according to court president Wang Zhenqing.
</P>
<P>
The reform was launched in response to a call from the Supreme
People's Court, which designated this year as a year for law
enforcement in light of the problem's status as the courts' No 1
headache, Wang said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
