<HEADLINE> Beijing Court Takes Lead in Addressing Enforcement Difficulties (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In accordance with the new approach, eight chief law
enforcement officers have been selected from the Enforcement
Division and each has been assigned three aides, all from the
division.
</P>
<P>
The chief law enforcement officials are to take full
responsibilities for the enforcement of court judgments assigned
to them and are empowered to make decisions related to the
enforcement by themselves, rather than subject all matters to the
director of the Enforcement Division as before, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
"As far as we know, this approach is a first in China," he said,
adding that "but this reform measure was carried out strictly in
line with the law."
</P>
<P>
The Chaoyang court has also decided to publicize the judgment
enforcement process, another new for Beijing's local courts.
</P>
<P>
All staff in the enforcement division were required to make
public their names and telephone numbers, subjecting themselves to
public oversight, Wang noted.
</P>
<P>
And every litigant will be offered a card to write down their
comments on the work of the assigned law enforcement officials.
</P>
<P>
The cards should be returned to the internal supervision
sections of the court and will serve as a major criterion to judge
the officials' performance.
</P>
<P>
"All theses measures are being taken to make sure enforcement
is fair and just," Wang claimed. 
</P>
