<DOCNO> XIE19990413.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: ABCs of Macao SAR Basic Law (27) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Following is part 27 of a
question and answer series on the Basic Law of the Macao Special
Administrative Region (MSAR).
</P>
<P>
Why is it that only permanent residents of Macao who are
Chinese citizens are eligible for assuming important posts such as
the chief executive of the MSAR?
</P>
<P>
It is expressly provided for in Article 25 of the Basic Law
that all Macao residents shall be equal before the law, and shall
be free from discrimination, irrespective of their nationality,
descent, race, sex, language, religion, political persuasion or
ideological belief, educational level, economic status or social
conditions.
</P>
<P>
A view has been expressed that the provision in the Basic Law
that only permanent residents of Macao who are Chinese citizens
are eligible for assuming the important posts such as the chief
executive of the MSAR discriminates against other permanent
residents who are not of Chinese nationality and contravenes the
principle that all are equal before the law. Such a view is
totally wrong.
</P>
<P>
All are equal before the law. This, as a legal principle, means
that everyone is equal before the laws already enacted. In other
words, it means that when the judicial bodies and other authorized
bodies apply law, all the parties involved must be treated on an
equal basis in strict accordance with law irrespective of their
social status. That is why "all are equal before the law" is often
referred by jurists as "all citizens are equal as far as the
application of law is concerned".
</P>
<P>
But the enacting of laws and the application of laws are not
the same thing. In enacting a law, the legislators concerned must
follow the established legislative principles and take into
account various social factors. It is not possible to have
absolute equality in this regard. For instance, it is in
accordance with the principle of state sovereignty that the Basic
Law requires that the important posts of the MSAR such as Chief
Executive must be served by Chinese citizens.
</P>
<P>
Similarly, it is in keeping with the principle of "Macao people
administering Macao" that the Basic Law classifies the Macao
residents into permanent residents and non-permanent residents and
requires that only permanent residents have the power to vote and
stand for election and can serve as members of the Legislative
Council and civil servants according to law. These provisions of
the Basic Law are designed to ensure the implementation of the
policy of "one country, two systems".
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990413.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sutton May Be out for Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Struggling Blackburn Rovers were
dealt a stunning blow with news that star striker Chris Sutton may
not play again this season.
</P>
<P>
