<HEADLINE> Deng Yaping Less Likely to Attend Sydney Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Table tennis queen Deng
Yaping distances herself from the 2000 Sydney Games as she opted
to study in Britain for the second time.
</P>
<P>
Deng, who now studies in the Beijing-based prestigious Qinghua
University, said on Tuesday that she will bound for Britain on
Thursday to study at the language center of the Nottingham
University for about one year.
</P>
<P>
The world and Olympic champion, who enrolled in Qinghua
University after the 1996 Atlanta Olympic Games, has spent over
seven months studying English in Cambridge University of Britain
before she came back to Qinghua early in August.
</P>
<P>
That she studies abroad for the second time strengthens the
belief that she has actually put an end to her playing career
although she promised an immeditate comeback to the national team
if necessary.
</P>
<P>
Deng did not appear in the line-up of the Chinese national
squad for the 45th world championships which was left in limbo for
the ongoing Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
Chinese head coach Cai Zhenhua said that no matter how
excellent they were, all players are required to go through the
tryout before they are qualified for major events.
</P>
<P>
Deng, 26, has been in semi-retirement since she completed a
singles-double sweep in the world championships in May 1996.
</P>
<P>
The veteran also did not attend the Asian Games where Chinese
paddlers swept six titles except the men's singles title. 
</P>
