<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Non-Government Companies Booming in Hi-Tech Parks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Non-government hi-tech companies
accounted for 80 percent of the total in 53 state and 58
provincial hi-tech industrial parks, according to statistics from
the Ministry of Science and Technology.
</P>
<P>
Most of the non-government science and technology enterprises
are involved in the hi-tech industries, which make them highly
competitive in research and development.
</P>
<P>
Many non-government-run hi-tech companies have already been
turning out large amounts of profits and revenue, while some
others are developing rapidly, according to today's Beijing
Science and Technology News.
</P>
<P>
The growth rate of output value of such enterprises is usually
higher than the average growth of local industry and agriculture.
The revenue from non-government-owned hi-tech enterprises in
Beijing surpassed 40 billion yuan (4.8 billion US dollars) in 1997,
or more than 70 percent of the total output value of the city's
industry.
</P>
<P>
Relevant departments are now expanding their efforts to create
a still better environment for the development of non-government-
owned companies, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2000, the total income of the non-government
enterprises will increase to 1,000 billion yuan (120 billion US
dollars) from the over 55 billion yuan in 1997, it will account
for some 10 percent of the national economy instead of six percent
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, there are a number of large non-government
scientific and technological enterprise companies springing up,
with quite a lot of them listed among the 500 most powerful
companies in the country.
</P>
<P>
The number of non-government hi-tech companies will also
increase by the end of this year to 100,000 from the 60,000 in
1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
