<DOCNO> XIE19990413.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Progress in China's Human Rights Conditions in 1998 (26) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The health level of children in China has been remarkably
improved. At present, there are 4,730 infant-friendly hospitals
across the country.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that by the end of 1997, China had achieved or
was going to realize 14 out of the 24 goals for the development of
children in the world by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The infant mortality rate and the mortality rate of children
under five years old stood at 33.1 and 42.3 per thousand
respectively. The infant mortality rate has dropped 40.9 per
thousand from the 74 per thousand of 20 years ago and the
mortality of children under five years old has also dropped by
about one-third.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the mortality of children suffering from diarrhea was
141.7 per 100,000, down 67.8 percent from 1991.
</P>
<P>
Some 3,371 rehabilitation centers have been built across the
country, with 4.16 million handicapped people recovering to
various degrees within ten years. Among them, 90,000 deaf children
have been able to speak, 600,000 children suffering from sequelae
of polio have improved their body function through orthopedics.
</P>
<P>
About 140,000 mentally retarded children have improved their
learning ability and ability to take care of themselves, through
rehabilitation training.
</P>
<P>
The State has funded the building of 91 children's welfare
institutes in urban areas, which have received more than 20,000
orphans.
</P>
<P>
China has eliminated the incidence of polio through a planned
immunization program. The project of putting iodine in salt and
providing iodine pills for more than 90 million pregnant women and
infants under two years old has reduced the incidence of the
handicapped caused by iodine-deficiency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990413.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Universities Start On-Line Enrollment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Students in China will soon be
able to apply for university places on-line and the whole system
could be up and running nationwide within three years, according
to sources from the Chinese Ministry of Education.
</P>
<P>
Universities and colleges in Beijing, Shanghai, Tianjin, and
Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, Liaoning and Sichuan Provinces
will try on-line enrollment this summer.
</P>
<P>
Enrollment offices will input applicants' files into computers
and transmit them through CERNET (Chinese Education and Research
Net) to universities and colleges. They will check the files for
suitability and issue admission or rejection slips accordingly.
</P>
<P>
However, some officials have expressed concern about on-line
enrollment. They are fearful that with so many universities and
colleges enrolling students at almost the same time there could be
a jam on the cyber-superhighway. They also point out that not all
universities in China are linked to the CERNET, especially those
in remote areas.
</P>
<P>
But other experts acknowledge that on-line enrollment will make
competition for university entrance more fair as it opens up the
system.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the Ministry of Education say that the on-line
applications will come under the direct supervision of the
admission committees of the relevant universities.
</P>
<P>
China will enroll 1.3 million college students this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
