<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Regional Early-Warning Weather System Operational </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- A regional early-warning system
to predict bad weather such as torrential rains, strong winds,
heavy thunderstorms and hailstones has become operational in
Beijing and covers the capital and surrounding areas in north
China.
</P>
<P>
The Science and Technology Daily has reported that the system
is made up of two parts: forecasting and monitoring.
</P>
<P>
The monitoring system includes a network covering northern
China, the Beijing ground observation network, the automatic
network for Beijing's urban areas and radar stations.
</P>
<P>
The range covers medium-scale weather forecasts, radar
recognition of inclement weather and devices for checking rainfall
levels.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Meteorological Bureau has established 12 automatic
stations which can automatically record wind direction and speed,
temperature and precipitation.
</P>
<P>
The early-warning system can also provide the time and scale of
imminent weather disasters, which is of vital importance for flood
prevention and effective communications to tackle the emergencies.
It also means that municipal policy-makers can be forewarned of
approaching disasters.
</P>
<P>
Scientists at the China Meteorological Administration and
Chinese Academy of Sciences have also launched a research program
focusing on methods for forecasting major weather disasters.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to reduce the heavy loss of life and property, China
now intends to introduce a nationwide early warning system to
predict torrential rains and other major weather disasters based
on this research.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
