<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bigger Judocas Carry China's Olympics Hope </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUILIN, Guangxi, April 13 (Xinhua) -- One judo gold medal in
each Olympic Games is not satiesfatory for China as it is going
into the 2000 Sydney Games.
</P>
<P>
Some talented bigger judocas from the women's section envital
higher golds hopes in the Games, but the ambitious Chinese are
awared of a rough-and-tough road stretching ahead.
</P>
<P>
Song Zhaonian, vice president of the Chinese Judo Association,
said here in the national championships: "We are concentrating our
golds hopes on athletes from above the 63-kilogram categories,
especially in the over-78kg class."
</P>
<P>
China has won two heavyweight Olympics golds from Zhuang
Xiaoyan in the 1992 Barcelona Games (over-72kg then) and from Sun
Fuming in Atlanta in 1996.
</P>
<P>
In the Bangkok Asian Games last December, China pocketed home
three golds and one silver from the 63kg, 70kg, under-78kg and
over-78kg classes.
</P>
<P>
Japan and South Korea, who dominated the smaller grades in the
Asian Games, hardly piled up any challenges to the bigger-sized
Chinese women. But the Europeans are the headaches.
</P>
<P>
"The European judocas are developing very fast in the past one
or two years," said Song, who just came back from a 15-day
European tour, "There will be no easy bout on the way to the 2000
Olympics from the qualifying competitions to the finals."
</P>
<P>
"We've lost our overwelming dominance in the heavyweight
category. We must be very careful on every step to the achievement
of our gold medals goal," Song added.
</P>
<P>
A domestic three-stop qualifying series was set up to choose
athletes for the world championship in Britain in October. The
national championship is just one of the three competitions of the
series.
</P>
<P>
Top three judocas with the best combined results from the three
competitions and some international champions need a final
selecting tournament to decide the judoca taking part in the world
championships.
</P>
<P>
"We want to compete in every category in the Sydney Games,"
Song said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
