<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two New Securities Funds Issued in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- China's two newly approved
securities investment funds, Taihe and Tongyi, offered 1.94
billion shares each at a price of one yuan to the public through
the Shanghai and Shenzhen stock exchanges, respectively, and sold
them all, according to Shanghai Securities News reports.
</P>
<P>
The Taihe Fund received subscriptions for 41.0 billion units,
and the Tongyi Fund received subscriptions for 22.7 billion units,
but only the people who won the lottery for the right to own the 1.
94 billion shares are now shareholders.
</P>
<P>
The unsuccessful lottery applicants all had their money
returned to them. The founders of the two companies retained the
rights to 60 million shares for each company.
</P>
<P>
The Taihe Fund was founded by the Guangfa Securities Co. Ltd.,
the Beijing Securities Co. Ltd., and the Jilin Trust and
Investment Company, among others.
</P>
<P>
The Tongyi Fund was founded by the Zhongxin Securities Co. Ltd.,
the Hubei Securities Co. Ltd., and others.
</P>
<P>
Analysts note that the two new funds drew total subscription
money of 64 billion yuan, which was remarkably less than that for
the six funds issued last year.
</P>
<P>
Of those six funds, the Yuyang Fund received the biggest
subscription, an awesome of 166.5 billion yuan, and the sixth
largest itself drew over 100 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say this was because when the six funds were issued
last year, they were a relatively new thing for Chinese investors,
and expectations for quick profit were unrealistic. They said
that after one year's performances, investors have become more
rational and realize that securities investment funds are long-
term investment tools and are not for short-term speculation.
</P>
<P>
Ding Wei, a spokesman for the Changsheng Fund Management Co.
Ltd., and manager of the Tongyi Fund, acknowledged that investors
have been less enthusiastic than they were last year.
</P>
<P>
This was good news for subscribers, he said, as they will have
a better chance in the lottery bidding.
</P>
<P>
And Ding denied that investors have been discouraged by the
funds' performance last year, noting that all the funds did quite
well, in view of the poor macroeconomic situation and the bearish
stock market.
</P>
<P>
The fact that the Tongyi Fund was issued on Friday, while two
new stocks will be offered to the public the next Monday should
also be considered, he said, adding that if an investors
subscribed to these latest funds, his capital would be frozen
until Monday, which would make it impossible for him to buy the
new stocks.
</P>
<P>
He concluded that as a long-term investment tool, securities
investment funds will prove good value and be welcomed by more and
more Chinese investors.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990413.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ Risks Becoming Australia's Economic Colony: Labor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, April 13 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand has been warned of
the danger of becoming an economic colony of Australia.
</P>
<P>
Local media Tuesday quoted Financial spokesman Michael Cullen
of the Labor Party, the major opposition party in the country, as
saying that the number of companies moving to Australia will
become a flood unless New Zealand shakes off the shackles of its
commodity-based economy and embraces the technological revolution.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports showed that Fernz Corporation, which is New
Zealand's ninth largest listed company and an Auckland-based
multinational chemicals company, is considering to move its head
office to Melbourne.
</P>
<P>
"We are seeing major companies moving headquarters to
Australia," Cullen said. "There is a very real risk in the next 10
years that that movement will become a flood, and that we will
simply become a series of branch offices and warehouses for the
Australian economy."
</P>
<P>
New Zealand is "in danger of becoming an economic colony of
Australia", Cullen warned.
</P>
<P>
He noted that New Zealand needs to make the transition to a
more knowledge-, skill- and technology-based economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
