<DOCNO> XIE19990413.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Malaysia on Track Towards Y2K Compliance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia is in a rush to be
Y2K compliant as the new millennium is approaching, and is
progressing well towards the millennium bug rectification.
</P>
<P>
Placing priority on the Y2K issue, the government has formed a
National Y2K Steering Committee under the Energy, Communications
and Multimedia Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The government has set aside 850 million ringgit (224 million
U.S. dollars), about 124 million U.S. dollars from its own and
another 100 million U.S. dollars from the World Bank as loans, in
undertaking projects to overcome the millennium bug.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the Securities Commission organized a conference on
Y2K as part of its effort to encourage companies to be Y2K
compliant and to create awareness of the millennium bug problem.
</P>
<P>
Earlier last month, the Energy, Communications and Multimedia
Ministry, in cooperation with NatSeven TV (NTV7), also launched a
national Y2K advertising campaign to enhance the public
understanding of the problem.
</P>
<P>
At Monday's conference, First Finance Minister Tun Daim
Zainuddin said the government recognized the importance of the Y2K
problem and is giving it its full attention in efforts to complete
preparations to face the year 2000 millennium bug.
</P>
<P>
He said the country is working on a framework for a national
Y2K contingency plan which provides a comprehensive blueprint for
the development of realistic and effective contingency plans at
both the sectoral and national levels.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that a complete set of the details of the
national plan, which highlights the scope of work that needs to
be done by all parties to address the problem and also what needs
to be done on and after January 1, 2000, will be ready by June
this year.
</P>
<P>
In addressing the Y2K problem, Malaysia's focus is on critical
sectors and agencies whose services affect public safety and
security. The critical sectors identified by the National Y2K
Project Team are energy, telecommunications, banking and
insurance, transportation, health, oil and gas, water supply, and
sewerage.
</P>
<P>
Energy, Communications and Multimedia Minister Leo Moggie
recently described the overall progress as "very satisfactory" as
60 to 65 percent of all the 113 organizations from the eight
critical sectors are Y2K-ready.
</P>
<P>
The banking sector is more at the forefront of Y2k
rectification. According to Bank Negara (Central Bank), which has
adopted a proactive approach to confront the Y2K problem, 74 out
of 77 banking institutions have completed all the three stages of
assessment, renovation and testing in compliance with the Y2K
requirements.
</P>
<P>
Most stockbroking companies in the country, or 78.1 percent of
the total 61, are also ready for Y2K, the Kuala Lumpur Stock
Exchange (KLSE) said in a statement Monday, adding that 93.8
percent would be Y2K ready by the second quarter of 1999 and 95.3
percent by the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the KLSE said that of the 457 main board companies
on the KLSE market, 64.1 percent is expected to be Y2K ready by
the second quarter of 1999, 81.4 percent by the following quarter
and 87.1 percent by the last quarter. While from a total of 282
second board companies, 68.8 percent is expected to be Y2K ready
by the second quarter, 84.4 percent by the third quarter and 91.5
percent by the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
The KLSE pledged to continue to monitor the state of Y2K
readiness of public-listed companies and will ensure the timely
disclosure of their Y2K readiness to the investing public.
</P>
<P>
Bank Negara expects full compliance from public-listed
companies and banks by the middle of this year.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's small and medium scale industries (SMIs), which are
said to be most vulnerable to the Y2K problem, have also been
given special attention in this regard because of their
significant position.
</P>
<P>
Bank Negara allocated 1.5 billion ringgit (394.736 million U.S.
dollars) as loans for SMIs to apply for solving their Y2K problem.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia is seen as one of the countries that have made heavy
investments in the area of the Y2K rectification and made
advantageous preparations to make sure there would not be any real
crisis when the new millennium comes.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said Malaysia's priority on the Y2K issue and its fast
action on the problem have given it an edge over many of its
neighbors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990413.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
