<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Airlines' Fare Hike Collapses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Some major U.S. airlines
Monday gave up their attempts to raise fares, thus the Continental
Airlines-led overall fare increase over the weekend collapsed.
</P>
<P>
Continental Airlines Inc., the nation's fifth-largest carrier,
announced Friday an across-the-board three percent fare increase
for leisure travel and one percent boost for walk-up tickets. The
move was quickly matched by United Airlines, the world's largest
airlines, and Delta Airlines, the nation's third largest.
</P>
<P>
But American Airlines, the world's second largest, and
Northwest Airlines, the nation's fourth largest, said they would
not follow suit.
</P>
<P>
And then, Delta, United and Continental said they pulled back
from the increase over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Airlines typically pull back from an increase in order to
remain competitive if other carriers do not follow suit.
</P>
<P>
But rising fuel prices and slowing revenue growth caused by a
drop in full-fare business travel are likely to force carriers to
try again soon for an increase, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
"With fuel prices up this year versus last year, that's an
incentive for airlines to try to go ahead" and raise fares, said
Brian Harris, airline analyst at Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
Airlines' shares were all down Monday, with United Airlines
shares down 1.1875 U.S. dollars to 77.75 dollars, American
Airlines down 2.0625 dollars to 66.3125 dollars, Delta down 2.0625
dollars to 69.50 dollars, Northwest down 1.0625 dollars to 28.1875
dollars and Continental down 1.3125 dollars to 39.5625 dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990413.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Home Depot to Double Store Numbers by 2002 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Home Depot, the world's
largest building products retailer, said Monday the company will
double the number of stores it operates by 2002, from its current
789 building supply stores.
</P>
<P>
"We expect our 21 percent growth rate to continue, and we will
end up with 1,600 stores in our system by the year 2002," said
Marshall Day, senior vice president for finance and accounting, at
a conference in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
The company's current 789 stores are mostly in the United
States, with more than 40 in Canada. Executives of the company
said it is now ready to begin a broader assault on markets outside
the United States.
</P>
<P>
"We are making plans for international growth. We are going to
take a very deliberate approach," Home Depot's Chief Financial
Officer Dennis Carey told 300 institutional investors at the same
conference Monday.
</P>
<P>
The traditionally big-bucks retailer also has plans to begin
selling products on-line from its Internet site in mid-1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
