<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia to Study Yugoslavia's Plea to Join Russia-Belarus Union </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Russia is positive towards
Yugoslavia's plea to join the Russia-Belarus union but will review
the issue closely, a spokesman quoted Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov
as saying on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov spoke highly of the Yugoslav application to enter the
union between fellow-Slav countries, but Russian leaders will
seriously consider the matter, the spokesman told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Yuli Yarov, chairman of the Executive Committee of the
Commonwealth of Independent States, told the media in Minsk on
Monday that Yugoslavia's entry into the union is a problem
difficult to resolve in a short time, saying it is a grave
political problem which needs to be taken seriously.
</P>
<P>
Even if the three countries -- Russia, Belarus and Yugoslavia --
formed a loose federation, there would be a long way to go, Yarov
said. He said the forthcoming parliamentary meeting of the Russia-
Belarus union will not discuss the matter.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, Moscow Mayor Yuli Luzhkov, who has a
considerable influence in the country's political circle,
expressed support for a three-country union.
</P>
<P>
But he insisted that it should occur after the end of the
Balkans war, adding that otherwise it would mean Russia is
voluntarily involved in the crisis, which will trigger another
round of military conflicts in the region.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Central Committee of the Russian Communist
Party Gennady Zyuganov affirmed that the Russian Communist party
and all patriotic forces will stand by Yugoslavia's bid to join
the union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
