<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0530 GMT April 13 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO -- Stock prices fell sharply in Tokyo Monday, dragged
down by profit-taking following sharp gains over the previous five
trading days.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange-issue declined 348.23 points,
or 2.07 percent, from last Friday's close to end at 16,507.40.
</P>
<P>
The index had gained more than 560 points over the previous
five trading days, and it briefly topped 17,000 Friday for the
first time in more than a year.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, dropped 26.71 percent or 1.99 percent to 1,
316.20. (Japan-Stock)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SINGAPORE -- The United States, Japan, the World Bank and the
Asian Development Bank (ADB) have promised to work together to
initially mobilize 5 billion U.S. dollars in bilateral and
multilateral support of bank and corporate restructuring in crisis-
hit Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Under-Secretary Timothy Geithner said a key element of the
strategy to accelerate the pace of bank and corporate
restructuring in the region is the Asian Growth and Recovery
Program (AGRP), which would be financed in part by the World Bank,
the ADB and bilateral support of various forms.
</P>
<P>
The AGRP would utilize innovative, cost-effective financing
methods to mobilize substantial additional private capital to
assist governments in the region to finance bank recapitalization,
he said. (Asia-Financial Support)
</P>
