<HEADLINE> Slaney Appeals against IAAF over Doping Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Former world champion Mary
Slaney filed a suit on Monday against the International Amateur
Athletics Federation (IAAF) and U.S. Olympic Committee(USOC),
accusing them of negligence and fraud in the handling of her 1996
doping case.
</P>
<P>
The 1,500 and 3,000 meters champion also attempted to halt an
arbitration hearing against her and prevent the IAAF and USOC
using a testosterone ratio as proof of doping by women athletes.
</P>
<P>
In the lawsuit, filed in U.S. District Court in Indianapolis,
USOC was accused of failing to ensure that Slaney's 1996 urine
sample was properly stored.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the lawsuit says the USOC's duty to protect Slaney
was breached when it used a testosterone to epitestosterone ratio
"as proxy for doping in women" and in the manner it analysed,
probed and supervised the investigation of Slaney's sample.
</P>
<P>
The legal action comes less than two weeks before the IAAF is
scheduled to resume an arbitration hearing in Monte Carlo on an
elevated testosterone to epitestosterone ratio found in a urine
sample provided by Slaney at the 1996 U.S. Olympic trials in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
A hearing board of USA Track and Field reinstated the former
world champion in 1999, saying "No doping violation has occurred."
</P>
<P>
But the IAAF decided to continue pursuing the case, referring
it to the arbitration panel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
