<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Conducts Census in Jaffna </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 13 (Xinhua) -- An official census is being taken
in Sri Lanka's northern Jaffna district for administrative
purposes, reports reaching here said Tuesday, quoting government
officials.
</P>
<P>
The reports said the census would be staggered, with the first
phase of the census currently in progress in the administrative
divisions of Jaffna town, Nallur and Koppay.
</P>
<P>
Census forms in Tamil and Sinhala are being distributed by
village officers in their respective areas and army officers will
collect the forms completed by each family in their divisions.
</P>
<P>
The army says correct statistics of the Jaffna population is
necessary to manage the security of the peninsula with greater
efficiency.
</P>
<P>
Jaffna peninsula, the former stronghold of Tamil rebels, was
recaptured by the army in 1996 in a civil war which has been waged
since 1983.
</P>
<P>
The last official census of Sri Lanka, including Jaffna, was
taken in 1981. Sri Lanka is scheduled to take a census of the
country in March 2001. 
</P>
