<HEADLINE> Bulgaria Protests Romania's Racketeering of Tourists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Bulgarian Interior Minister Bogomil
Bonev has voiced protests against racketeering by Romanian
officials towards Bulgarian travelers, official sources told the
Bulgarian news agency BTA on Monday.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to his Romanian counterpart Constantin Dudu Ionescu,
Bonev said that in the past two weeks the number of complaints
about criminal actions conducted by Romanian officials towards
Bulgarian travelers has greatly increased.
</P>
<P>
In their complaints, the claimants said that charges and fines
were levied and collected from Bulgarians without specifying the
reasons or providing receipts. They said this has been taking
place along the border and inside Romania.
</P>
<P>
Tourists also complained that during their travels in Romania,
they were stopped on a number of occasions by Romanian policemen
under the pretext to check passports, and then they were required
to pay fines or fees, mostly between 20 and 50 Deutsche marks.
</P>
<P>
Bonev said that Bulgaria is aware of the difficulties and
problems the Romanian police are experiencing because of the
increased traffic along the Bulgarian-Romanian border following
the refugee crisis in Yugoslavia, but it also considers predatory
"racketeering" by public officials to be unacceptable under any
conditions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
