<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodia Govt to Crack Down Illegal Fishing on Mekong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The Cambodian government is
determined to take tough measures to stop illegal fishing now "in
a state of anarchy" in Mekong River and Tonle Sap Lake, local
reports said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Council of Ministers warned last week that a failure to
take actions could lead to the virtual extinction of fish in some
Cambodian waters.
</P>
<P>
The directive instructed the co-ministers of Defense and
Interior, the Royal Cambodian Armed Forces (RCAF)
commander-in-chief, police directors, and all levels of local
authorities to "take strict and suitable measures against armed
men who get involved in fishing offshores."
</P>
<P>
The government's new directive also called for a crackdown on
fishing out of season, selling baby fish to foreign countries, and
on foreign boats fishing in Cambodian waters.
</P>
<P>
A fisheries expert estimated recently that more than 100
motorized illegal trawlers regularly ply the waters of Mekong
River between Kandal and Kompong Cham provinces. They were able to
do so by paying as much as 400 U.S. dollars a day in bribes, a
government official was quoted by the Cambodia Daily as saying
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Overfishing has become a mounting concern in recent years, as
the number of fish has steadily decreased. Fish stocks are now
believed to be at an all-time low. Enforcement of the nation's
fishing law has been stymied by corruption and lack of resources.
</P>
<P>
The government measures are expected to at least prevent
anarchic activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990413.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Progress in China's Human Rights Conditions in 1998 (17) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
IV. Citizen's Economic, Social and Cultural Rights
</P>
<P>
China attaches great importance to the protection of citizen's
labor and social security rights. In order to protect citizen's
rights of employment, the state offers employment services and
directions through developing various employment agencies, creates
jobs, opens job training classes and adopts many other measures to
promote the workers' employment and re-employment.
</P>
<P>
Over the past two decades, with the economic development, China
has created non-agricultural jobs of more than 250 million, and
130 million laborers have been changed from the agricultural to
non-agricultural sector.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, China had established over 34,000
employment agencies. With their help, a total of 8.737 million
people found jobs that year. The registered unemployment rate in
cities and towns was 3.1 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
A re-employment project aiming to solve the problem of the
jobless and the laid-off workers was initiated in 1994, and has
been carried out nationwide.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1998, all of the state-owned enterprises with
laid-off workers had set up re-employment service centers and 99
percent of the laid-off workers had registered with the centers,
with 93.2 percent of them receiving living expenses from the
centers. With the help of the re-employment project, 10.425
million workers laid off by state-owned enterprises were re-
employed in 1997 and 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
