<HEADLINE> Bangkok Hotels See Signs of Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Pushed by a boom in tourism,
occupancy rates in Bangkok hotels are steadily rising as the
economy begins to revive slowly, a leading Thai hotelier said.
</P>
<P>
Most hotels were reporting occupancy rates of about 60 percent,
while international train hotels were doing even better, Prakit
Chinamornphong, secretary of the Thai hotels Association, said in
remarks published by Tuesday's Bangkok Post.
</P>
<P>
The last three years have been hard on Bangkok hoteliers, with
several new properties opening just as the economy started to
slump. The struggle to fill 65,000 rooms led to price wars, but
tourist stays in the capital declined because of concern about
traffic and pollution.
</P>
<P>
Many hotel owners, most of them well-known business families in
need of cash to pay down debts, have put their properties up for
sale. Foreign investors have been shopping, but the prices they're
offering don't match owners' expectations.
</P>
<P>
But the situation has been changed for the better. "Foreign
tourists and business travelers are beginning to come as Thailand
is gradually becoming well-known because of the Amazing Thailand
campaign," Jan Heesbeen, director of marketing for the JW Marriot
Hotel, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Meanwhile the government continues to promote and advertise
the country, and the cheap baht is attracting foreigners to shop
and visit," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Moreover, Thailand, particularly Bangkok, has not stopped
developing its basic infrastructure, while other capitals in this
region have stopped their projects," he said.
</P>
<P>
"During the first three months of this year, we attracted more
international meetings from this region. The upturn in the economy
and the stable foreign exchange rate is bringing back business and
the trend for the hotel industry in Bangkok is slowly heading up,"
Heesbeen said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
