<HEADLINE> CSKA Goalkeeper and Captain Attacked in Bulgaria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- CSKA goalkeeper Ivailo Ivanov and
Captain Adalbert Zafirov were attacked when they emerged from the
changing rooms after the half time break of the match between CSKA
and Levski-Kyustendil played on April 11.
</P>
<P>
Protests were issued after the controversial match between the
two teams.
</P>
<P>
In the last match of the 22nd round of the first division of
the national football championship in Kyustendil, the CSKA players
failed to come out after the half time break. They led 1-0
against their hosts.
</P>
<P>
The management of the football club said that CSKA goalkeeper
Ivailo Ivanov and Captain Adalbert Zafirov were attacked by
unknown persons when they emerged from the changing rooms.
</P>
<P>
The players of Levski-Kyustendil and their fans denied any
violence and accused their opponents with unworthy performance.
</P>
<P>
In a special statement CSKA President Iliya Pavlov said that
what happened "has gone beyond any norms of sport competition,
sportsmanship and normal human relations".
</P>
<P>
According to Pavlov, the beating of Zafirov and Ivanov is not
only an unprecedented act of hooliganism but an organized
violation against sport. Pavlov described as an alarming fact
that at time the brutal act was committed the law-enforcement
officials were absent from their position.
</P>
<P>
CSKA Football Club Executive Director Georgi Hristov said that
the club will fight for its rights to the end as the result of the
match will be taken into account by all the clubs in Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
"We can approach the UEFA committees if we have to," Hristov
told a special news conference about the accident.
</P>
<P>
Already on Sunday the Interior Ministry said that Head of the
National Police Service General Vassil Vassilev has ordered an
immediate investigation of the event. 
</P>
</TEXT>
