<HEADLINE> Thai Govt to Cut Import Duties For Various Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's Finance Ministry is
working on cutting import duties for various products to help
domestic manufacturers reduce their production costs, the Nation
newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the ministry said the government will soon
announce the cut in import duties as a follow-up to an economic
stimulus package announced on March 30.
</P>
<P>
He said the duties will be cut from the current range of 0
percent to 30 percent to a new range of 0 percent to 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
About nine categories of goods will be eligible for the cut,
and their average tax rate will fall by half from the current 17
percent.
</P>
<P>
Most of the duties for raw materiel will be cut to 0 percent.
</P>
<P>
He said the planned cut in import duties will reduce the
government's tax revenue in the range of 10 billion baht (270
million U.S. dollars) a year. 
</P>
