<HEADLINE> EDS-Updates with details Colombian Government Confirms Avianca Plane Hijacking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The Colombian government confirmed
on Monday night that an Avianca airlines plane had been hijacked,
saying that all the 41 passengers and five crew members aboard
were led into the forest 500 kilometers north of Bogota.
</P>
<P>
The government did not specify the hijackers or the reasons why
they led the hostages into the forest.
</P>
<P>
"No one has claimed responsibility for this act," the
government said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Air Force General Hector Velasco told local radio stations that
search helicopters had spotted the plane, which disappeared from
radar screens minutes after taking off from the northeastern city
of Bucaramanga.
</P>
<P>
The Fokker-50 plane was reported missing an hour after failing
to land at the Eldorado international airport at Bogota, a 45-
minute flight from Bucaramanga.
</P>
<P>
Ernesto Huertas, head of Colombia's civil aviation authority,
Aerocivil, said the Fokker was found "in excellent condition on an
airstrip called Los Avalos," near the town of Simiti.
</P>
<P>
"Police were on the runway, entered the plane, but did not find
any passengers or crew," he said. "We have no further information.
"
</P>
<P>
The area has been the scene of activities of the country's
leftist guerrillas of the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia
and rebels of the National Liberation Army. However, neither rebel
group claimed responsibility for the disappearance of the
passengers and crew.
</P>
<P>
General Rafael Hernandez, chairman of the joint chiefs of staff,
said the search efforts would continue to rescue the "kidnapped
occupants" of the plane. 
</P>
</TEXT>
