<HEADLINE> Panamanian Writers Condemn NATO Bombings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Panamanian writers Monday
condemned NATO's bombings against Yugoslavia and called for a
diplomatic solution within the framework of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
"The bombings that are being carried out indiscriminately by
NATO forces against Yugoslavia form a violation of the
international rights established in the Charter of the United
Nations," said writer Luis Carlos Jimenez.
</P>
<P>
The Panamanian writer, who has published his poetry work in
Colombia, the United States, Mexico and Central America, held that
the United States has no right to intervene in the internal
affairs of a sovereign country.
</P>
<P>
"The argument used by NATO for this military interference in
Yugoslavia is so weak that voices of protest have been raised even
in the very member countries of the alliance," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ethnic Albanians are fleeing Kosovo in large numbers since the
NATO alliance started the bombing 19 days ago to force Yugoslavia
to agree to a peace plan for Kosovo, a province of Yugoslavia's
Serbian Republic.
</P>
<P>
Panamanian poet and novelist Jose Franco also condemned NATO's
indiscriminate bombing in Yugoslavia and accused it of causing an
exodus of refugees.
</P>
<P>
"I don't agree with the violence that has been unleashed
against this Balkan country and I condemn NATO's bombing," said
the Panamanian author, who twice won the Miro Prize, the biggest
literary prize of this country.
</P>
<P>
"We know how a war begins, but one never knows how it will end,
" added Franco. 
</P>
</TEXT>
