<HEADLINE> China to Quadruple Consumption of Natural Gas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- China will quadruple consumption
of natural gas in about a decade out of concern for worsening
environmental pollution, according to the State Administration of
Petroleum and Chemicals (SAPC).
</P>
<P>
Long-distance pipelines are to be built for gas transmission
from China's gas-rich western areas to the east and the south
where energy resources are in shortage while the demand is great,
said officials at a two-day seminar opened yesterday in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Chen Geng, deputy director of the SAPC, was quoted by Tuesday's
China Daily as saying that foreign investors will be invited to
participate in long-distance pipeline construction at the seminar.
</P>
<P>
Opportunities for foreign investors may come for building a gas
pipeline to stretch thousands of kilometers from Russia to China
as the Chinese government is considering introduction of Russian
gas, according to Chen.
</P>
<P>
The French oil giant Total and Gaz de France, which is hosting
the China-France Gas Industry Policy Seminar together with China
National Petroleum Corp, are among the firms that wish to
participate in China's gas programs.
</P>
<P>
Natural gas now accounts for only 2 percent of energy
consumption in China, compared with the 23 percent world average.
In contrast, coal, which tends to pollute heavily when transformed
into energy, supplies 75 percent of China's energy.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government is considering policy support in
taxation and pricing, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, subsidies may compensate end-users as the country
will have to maintain high natural gas prices to ensure
developers' revenues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
