<HEADLINE> Panama Deplores NATO Attacks Against Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The Panamanian government
deplores the use of force by NATO in Yugoslavia, Foreign Minister
Jose Eduardo Ritter said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Panama adheres to the position adopted recently by the
countries of the Rio Group, which rejects the use of violence to
solve the ethnic conflict in the Yugoslav province of Kosovo," he
said at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
He said his government is worried about the refugees situation
in Kosovo, adding, "We are closely following the removal of
refugees."
</P>
<P>
Recalling Panama's benefits from the diplomatic solution of the
Panama Canal problem, the minister urged parties concerned to
start dialogue to solve the Kosovo problem.
</P>
<P>
"Panama deplores the use of force because it itself has taken
advantage of peaceful means to solve the Panama Canal Problem," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Panama signed the Torrijos-Carter Treaty with the United States
in 1977, with which it leveled the way for the Canal's recovery
from the U.S. with the help of the UN.
</P>
<P>
According to the treaty the United States will return the canal
to Panamanian sovereignty on December 31, 1999, and before this
date, it should withdraw its troops after almost 70 years of
military occupation. 
</P>
