<HEADLINE> Shaanxi Steps up Construction of Agricultural Hi-Tech Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, April 13 (Xinhua) -- An agricultural hi-tech zone in
Shaanxi Province, which was set up as a demonstration zone for dry
farming in northwest China, is making progress.
</P>
<P>
Founded in July of 1997, the Yangling hi-tech zone, 82 km east
of the provincial capital of Xi'an, covers an area of 22.12 sq km.
It is becoming the country's most important research base for dry
farming.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2002, the zone's gross domestic product will reach
about 2 billion yuan, according to Zhang Guangqiang, deputy
secretary general of the provincial government.
</P>
<P>
Irrigated farmland in northwest China makes up one-third of the
country's total. However, farm production of the area is backward
due to drought and lack of water.
</P>
<P>
So far, the zone has forged cooperation ties with Israel, the
United States and Japan.
</P>
<P>
It has also reached an agreement with a Hong Kong firm on the
establishment of a farm technology development company, which will
involve 10 million yuan in investment from each side.
</P>
<P>
Thus far, the zone has approved 85 projects involving a total
investment of 2.85 billion yuan. Output value of the zone will
exceed 7 billion yuan a year with the operation of all the
projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
