<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia to Launch WTO Action on S.Korea Beef Measures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Australia will initiate dispute
action in the World Trade Organization (WTO) over import
restrictions on Australian beef exports to South Korea, Australian
deputy prime minister and trade minister Tim Fischer said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Given lack of progress on the issue we have been left with
little choice other than to initiate WTO action," Fischer said in
a statement.
</P>
<P>
He said that following a successful Australia challenge in 1989
under the then GATT system, South Korea had set in train import
liberalization measures and was required to undertake further
liberalization by 2001.
</P>
<P>
"Unfortunately, however, the pace of reform (in South Korea)
has stalled. In addition to tariff quotas, (South) Korea still
maintains a number of impediments on the sale of imported beef."
</P>
<P>
"Without a road map for dismantling those barriers, the 2001
objectives sanctioned by the GATT/WTO might not be achievable,"
Fischer said.
</P>
<P>
South Korea is Australia's third largest beef market worth an
average of 88 million U.S. dollars a year over the past five
years.
</P>
<P>
Fischer said the next step in the dispute with South Korea
would be to proceed with a panel request in May or June.
</P>
<P>
The United States is taking similar dispute action against
South Korea, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
