<DOCNO> XIE19990413.0309 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Economy Passes All IMF-set Standards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has met
all of the International Monetary Fund's first-quarter performance
criteria, or the economic indicators used to determine the
country's qualifications to avail itself of the Fund's facilities,
Business World reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Under the country's standby facility with the IMF, the
government must meet set targets on net international reserves
(NIR), foreign borrowings, domestic liquidity and public sector
borrowings.
</P>
<P>
Official government figures show that as of end-March, NIR --
the net foreign exchange position of the central bank and
commercial banks --stood at 9.847 billion U.S. dollars. This
translates to a 1.83 billion U.S. dollar surplus for the first
quarter, already in excess of the 1.6 billion U.S. dollar target
for the year.
</P>
<P>
On foreign borrowing, outstanding short-term borrowings in the
first quarter as recorded by the Central Bank stood at only 140
million U.S. dollars, or exactly 160 million dollar less than the
target for the period.
</P>
<P>
Borrowing with maturities of one to five years amounted to only
1.8 billion U.S. dollars during the period, or 400 million U.S.
dollars less than the 2.2 billion U.S. dollar target.
</P>
<P>
On domestic liquidity, the Central Bank reported that it has
kept base money and reserve money levels at 18 billion pesos (450
million U.S. dollars) and 30 billion pesos (750 million dollars)
respectively, below the ceilings set with the IMF for the first
three months.
</P>
<P>
Department of Finance simulations also show the government will
meet its 34.2-billion peso (855 million dollar) public sector
borrowing requirement target for the first three months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
