<HEADLINE> Thai PM Seeks Impartiality Over Race for WTO Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai has
appealed to Tanzania, which chairs the selection process for the
new chief of the World Trade Organization (WTO), for impartiality,
fairness and transparency to end the impasse between the
candidates from Thailand and New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
Thai Deputy Prime Minister Supachai Panitchpakdi is competing
with New Zealand's former prime minister Mike Moore to replace
Ranato Ruggierro as the WTO's new director-general.
</P>
<P>
Chuan made the call Monday during his meeting with the
Tanzanian ambassador to Thailand, Seif Ali Iddi, who called on him
to bid farewell after completing his term. The ambassador is
expected to convey Chuan's message to Ali Mchumo, chairmen of The
WTO's General Council, The Bangkok Post reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The 134 members of the WTO have missed four deadlines for a
consensus on the successor to WTO director-general Renato
Ruggierro, whose term expires on April.
</P>
<P>
The WTO General Council is due to meet on April 14 for what is
expected to be the final decision on the matter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
