<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' T-bill Rates Fall to Pre-crisis Levels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The yield on the Philippine
government's 91-day Treasury bill fell 51.5 points Monday as banks
aggressively pushed down interest rates in the wake of the latest
cut in the Central Bank's key overnight rates, the Business World
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the newspaper, the 91-day T-bill, which banks use
as a basis in pricing their loans, settled at 10.972 percent, the
first time it went below 11 percent since June 30, 1997, or just
before the start of the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
But while interest rates are falling, the national government
and monetary authorities are still not getting the desired
result-- an increase in bank lending which will eventually help
jump-start the economy.
</P>
<P>
Money market traders said banks flocked to Monday's auction,
indicating their desire to put their money in government
securities rather than face the risks of new loans.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said the Department of Finance is raising the
pressure on banks to lend by reducing anew the amount the
government borrows through the weekly T-bill auctions.
</P>
<P>
The government now borrows 5 billion pesos (125 million U.S.
dollars) weekly from banks through T-bills. It reduced the auction
size by 500 million pesos (12.5 million dollars) last month.
</P>
<P>
With less government securities to invest their funds in, banks
will have little alternative but to start lending to businesses.
</P>
<P>
Monetary authorities have also implemented a number of moves to
encourage banks to lend, including slashing key interest rates and
reducing their reserve requirements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
