<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 01:00 GMT April 13 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE -- NATO planes bombed an international passenger train
on a bridge 300 kilometers south of Belgrade Monday, killing at
least two people and injuring 14, the official Tanjug agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The international passenger train 393 en route from Belgrade
to Salonika, Greece, was hit at 11:49 a.m. while crossing a bridge
at Grdelicka Klisura. Two carriages were destroyed and two damaged,
the report said.(NATO-Train)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russia hopes that Palestine and Israel will reach an
agreement as early as possible on smoothly going through the
current critical period, Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov said here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov made the remarks at a joint press conference after
meeting with his Israeli counterpart Ariel Sharon.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov said that keeping peace in the region during the
transitional period will provide a new driving force for advancing
the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Sharon said he had indicated during their talks the danger of
Russia transferring nuclear technologies to Iran and other Middle
East countries and providing arms to Syria. (Russia-Palestine-
Moscow)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- U.S. Secretary of State Medeleine Albright said
here Monday that the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO)
needs "patience and perseverance" over the air strikes against
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
After NATO foreign ministers had their special meeting on
Kosovo crisis at the NATO headquarters in Brussels, Albright told
reporters that "what has become evident with the military campaign
is that it is systematically biding into and destroying the
machine of repression."
</P>
<P>
Reporters have been told there was no plans of ground troops
deployment. After the special ministerial meeting, reporters were
also told that the 19 foreign ministers of the alliance did not
talk about matters concerning ground troops. But some journalists
wondered if the ministers privately discussed certain aspects of
such deployment. (NATO-Yugoslavia)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
GENEVA -- China's accession to the World Trade Organization (
WTO) before the end of 1999 is vital both for China and the WTO,
said WTO Director-General Renato Ruggiero here Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The recent meeting of Chinese Prime Minister Zhu Rongji and U.
S. President Bill Clinton (in Washington) has brought the
negotiation for China's entry to the WTO very near its conclusion,
" Ruggiero told Xinhua in an exclusive interview.
</P>
<P>
"Seeing from the WTO point of view, it is also positive that a
full agreement has not been found on a bilateral basis," he said.
"We now have better conditions for achieving a multilateral
agreement which will lead China into the WTO before the end of
this year." 
</P>
