<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Limit Number of Laid-Off Workers to 7 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- China plans to limit the number
of workers laid off from State-owned enterprises to 7 million this
year, 1 million more than in 1998, China Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
Some 24.5 billion yuan (3 billion US dollars) will be needed to
take care of these workers this year, Wang Jianlun, vice-minister
of Labor and Social Security, told the daily.
</P>
<P>
Taking better care of laid-off workers and further expanding
coverage of the pension system are being given priority by the
ministry, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
Once laid off, workers enroll at enterprises-based re-
employment service centers, where they get a monthly allowance
ranging from 140 yuan to 380 yuan.
</P>
<P>
This allowance is paid by the government, the unemployment
insurance fund and the enterprises themselves, said Mo Rong, an
expert at the Institute of Labor Studies.
</P>
<P>
Laid-off workers can stay registered at a center for a maximum
of three years. They will be absorbed into the unemployment
insurance network if they fail to get a job with that period, Mo
said.
</P>
<P>
If they are still jobless after receiving unemployment
insurance for another two years, they will only be entitled to a
minimum allowance from funds run by the Ministry of Civil Affairs,
Mo said.
</P>
<P>
Turning to the pension system, Vice-Minister Wang said that, by
the end of June, the pension network should have expanded to cover
110 million people, 26 million more than 1998.
</P>
<P>
Since May last year, the bureaus of labor and social security
have been working to ensure pensions are paid on time and make up
for any delayed payments, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
Since September last year, 99 percent of retired workers
receive a monthly pension. some 3 billion yuan of delayed pensions
have been distributed to date, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
Enterprises are required to pay a contribution into employee'
pension accounts. Some unprofitable enterprises fail to pay their
share, and others simply shirk their responsibility. This led to a
shortage of pension funds, hence the delay in payment, Mo said.
</P>
<P>
A thorough check will be carried out to ensure at least 50
percent of the payment due is collected by the year end, Wang said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990413.0319 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Produces 3.4 Mln Barrels of Crude Oil in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar produced 3.423 million
barrels of crude oil in 1998, down 239,500 barrels from 1997,
according to the latest official Economic Indicators.
</P>
<P>
According to figures issued by the country's Central
Statistical Organization, the output of natural gas was 1.749
billion cubic-meters last year, a drop of 35 million cubic-meters
compared with 1997.
</P>
<P>
Up to the end of 1998, foreign investment in the oil and gas
sector coming from Australia, Britain, France, Indonesia, Japan,
Thailand and the United States reached 2.114 billion U.S. dollars
in 40 projects. The total foreign investment stood at 7.1 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Yetagun oil and natural gas field, one of Myanmar's main
fields of its kind, has a gas reserve of 33.96 billion
cubic-meters and oil reserve of 2 billion barrels.
</P>
<P>
According to a 30-year sale contract reached between the
developers and the Petroleum Authority of Thailand in March 1997,
the Yetagun gas will be exported to Thailand at 5.66 million
cubic-meters per day.
</P>
<P>
The gas field will go into production later this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
