<HEADLINE> U.S. to Form New Internet Policy Institute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The United States will set up
a new institute on global Internet policy and research later this
year, said a working group from the organization in a statement on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The 22 members of the group are from U.S. businesses,
nonprofit groups and academic institutions, which include the
Washington-based Highway 1, Nasdaq Stock Market, the Potomac
KnowledgeWay, Information Technology Association of America,
University of Maryland, University of Illinois, the Washington
Post, Microsoft and American Online.
</P>
<P>
The Internet Policy Institute will be an independent, nonprofit
research and educational organization chartered to provide
analysis, research, education, and outreach on a full range of
economic, social and policy issues affecting and affected by the
global development and use of the Internet, the statement noted.
</P>
<P>
The institute, which will begin operations when funding is
finalized and staff has been hired, will have a physical presence
in the Washington region and an active presence on the Internet,
where it can draw on the research being conducted on online issues
by scholars from around the world.
</P>
<P>
While its initial staffing is limited, the institute will
eventually add staff researchers and senior fellows, the group
said.
</P>
<P>
In the next months the group will establish an organizational
structure for the institute and begin reaching out to national and
non-U.S.-based companies and institutions for participation, the
statement said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
