<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian President Calls for Peace in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Italian President Oscar Luigi
Scalfaro said on Monday that a total commitment to its NATO allies
regarding the Kosovo crisis still left room for a determined
search for peace.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Quirinale presidential palace, Scalfaro
reiterated his contention that war had "never resolved anything"
and that the pursuit of peace was a moral duty.
</P>
<P>
"Italy, which is totally faithful to the pacts and accords it
has signed, has a desire and an inextinguishable cry for peace,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Italy has come under fire in certain quarters of the U.S.
government for not being a reliable ally and for allowing parallel
peace initiatives to be held even as NATO planes based in Italy
were taking off to conduct air strikes against Yugoslavia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
