<DOCNO> XIE19990413.0327 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Issues 1998 Human Rights Conditions (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The Information Office of the
State Council issued here today an article on China's 1998 human
rights conditions, noting that the protection and promotion of
people's rights to subsistence and development has been China's
top task in the field of human rights.
</P>
<P>
Entitled "Progress in China's Human Rights Cause in 1998," the
article said China's gross domestic product (GDP) increased by
nearly five times in the past two decades, with the per capita GDP
going up by 3.4 times.
</P>
<P>
Despite the effect of the deep impact of the Asian financial
crisis and the catastrophic floods, China managed to achieve a GDP
growth rate of 7.8 percent in 1998, the article noted.
</P>
<P>
The per capita income of the rural residents was 4.3 percent up
over the previous year in real terms, while the per capita
disposable income of urban residents increased by 5.8 percent in
real terms.
</P>
<P>
With the common efforts made by the government and the people
from all walks of life, another eight million rural people in
poverty-stricken areas met their basic need for food and clothing.
</P>
<P>
The country's total poverty-stricken population dropped from
250 million in 1978 to 42 million so far. China has witnessed the
quickest decrease in its poverty-stricken population more than any
other country in the world.
</P>
<P>
The 13,000-word article consists of seven parts: 1. People's
Rights to Subsistence and Development; 2. Guarantee of Citizens'
Political Rights; 3. Judicial Guarantee for Human Rights; 4.
Citizens' Economic, Social and Cultural Rights; 5. Legitimate
Rights and Interests of Women and Children; 6. Rights of Ethnic
Minority Groups; 7. Foreign Exchange and Cooperation in the Field
of Human Rights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990413.0328 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba, Panama Sign an Industrial Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 12 (Xinhua)-- Cuba and Panama signed an agreement
on industrial protection on Monday which will be useful in
protecting the interests of both nations.
</P>
<P>
Cuba's Science, Technology and Environmental Minister Elena
Simeon, and Panamanian Industry and Trade Minister Raul Hernandez
Lopez -- who arrived here Sunday night for a five-day visit --
signed the agreement.
</P>
<P>
The Panamanian minister said that his country's interest is to
move closer to Cuba's markets and facilitate business
opportunities for the island's firms.
</P>
<P>
Both officials discussed the structural transformation of the
isthmus' economy and the impact of the recovery of the Panama
Canal in the near future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
