<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Issues 1998 Human Rights Conditions (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
While promoting people's rights to subsistence and development,
the article said, China pays great attention to the building of a
democratic and legal system, and the protection of citizens'
political rights according to law.
</P>
<P>
The Ninth National People's Congress (NPC) and its Standing
Committee have adopted 24 laws and decisions concerning legal
issues since 1998.
</P>
<P>
At the second session of the Ninth NPC that was convened in
March 1999, the amendments was made to the current constitution by
adding the "rule of the country by law and building a socialist
legal state."
</P>
<P>
The elevation of the "rule of the country by law" into a
constitutional principle, which is a basic strategy in
administering the state affairs, is of great significance to
building a democratic and legal system and protecting human rights.
</P>
<P>
The article noted China has made eye-catching progress in
promoting democracy in grass-roots units in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Villages across the country conduct rural grass-roots mass self-
management activities that focus on villagers' democratic
elections, policy-making, management and supervision.
</P>
<P>
To date, the system of village autonomy has been established in
a preliminary fashion in 60 percent of China's villages.
</P>
<P>
The article stressed China has rigorously enforced the letter
of the law and strengthened human rights protection efforts in
every aspect of law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
Courts at all levels extended great efforts to promote open
trials and intensified social and media supervision over court
proceedings in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Trials of various major cases were televised or broadcast live.
So far, altogether 11 higher people's courts and 58 intermediate
courts have permitted televised broadcast of some cases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990413.0332 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Issues 1998 Human Rights Conditions (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The article said China attaches great importance to the
protection of citizens' labor and social security rights.
</P>
<P>
In order to protect citizens' rights of employment, the state
offers employment services and directions through developing
various employment agencies, creates jobs, opens job training
classes and adopts many other measures to promote the workers'
employment and reemployment.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1998, all of the state-owned enterprises with
laid-off workers had set up reemployment service centers, helping
99 percent of the layoffs, and 93.2 percent of the layoffs
received living expenses from the centers.
</P>
<P>
With the help of the reemployment projects, 10.425 million
workers laid off by the state-owned enterprises were reemployed in
1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, social relief and social welfare work has developed
steadily, the article said.
</P>
<P>
A system to ensure a minimum living standard for city residents
had been established in 600 cities and 1,242 counties by the end
of 1998, providing relief for more than 3.32 million people.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the article said, the right of Chinese citizens to
receive education has been further protected. The state has
increased investment in education, and vigorously created improved
educational conditions for citizens.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, an additional 360 counties, cities and districts met
the demand to make the nine years of compulsory education
universal and basically wipe out illiteracy among the young and
adults.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, some 6.08 million students including 180,000
postgraduates were studying in colleges and universities. The
gross enrollment rate of colleges and universities increased to 9.
07 percent, higher than the average level of the developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that 42.5 percent of China's population aged at
or above 25 have received secondary education, approaching the
level in the developed countries including the United States.  (
more)
nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990413.0333 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Issues 1998 Human Rights Conditions (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The article pointed out that an increasing number of Chinese
women have been involved in the management of the country's
political and social affairs.
</P>
<P>
There are 650 women deputies to the Ninth NPC and 341 female
members of the Ninth National Committee of the Chinese People's
Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC).
</P>
<P>
The number of women employees in China has increased as a
result of larger proportion of women employed than before.
According to a survey conducted by the International Labor
Organization in the United States, Russia, India and other 26
countries in 1998, the employment rate of Chinese women reached 56
percent, ranking first among all the other countries.
</P>
<P>
The rights of children are protected in accordance with law,
the article said.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, Project Hope helped 251,800 school dropouts and built
1,855 primary schools, while aiding 53,907 children from poor
families.
</P>
<P>
The article stressed all ethnic groups in China are equal and
the state offers preferential policies to ethnic minorities.
</P>
<P>
The ethnic minorities enjoy the right to participate in
administration of the country and their own groups. All the 55
ethnic minority groups have their representatives and members in
the Ninth NPC and CPPCC National Committee.
</P>
<P>
Officials with ethnic minority background amounted to 2.5
million in China today. In 1998, Tibetan officials made up of 74.9
percent of all officials in the Tibet Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The state offers the areas inhabited by ethnic minorities with
policy preference as well as funds, technologies and skilled
professionals for the socioeconomic development there.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the financial subsidies to the Tibet
Autonomous Region by the central government surpassed 1.2 billion
yuan (about 144.6 million U.S. dollars) each year.
</P>
<P>
Statistics indicates that over the past five consecutive years,
Tibet has registered an annual economic growth rate of 12.9
percent, which surpassed that of the national average for two
successive years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990413.0334 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Issues 1998 Human Rights Conditions (5) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The article said the Chinese government has always attached
great importance to international human rights covenants, which
are regarded as playing an active role in promoting the progress
of human rights.
</P>
<P>
China has so far signed a total of 17 international covenants
on human rights and tried all out to implement the covenants which
China has joined.
</P>
<P>
On the above basis, the Chinese government signed the
International Covenant on Economic, Social and Cultural Rights in
October 1997 and the International Covenant on Civil and Political
Rights in October 1998.
</P>
<P>
China is now studying and deliberating the two covenants in
accordance with the Constitution and concerned laws.
</P>
<P>
The same as the rest of the world, China has many problems
which should be solved in the field of human rights, the article
said, adding that the Chinese government is willing to learn from
other countries' useful experience in promoting human rights.
</P>
<P>
China will persistently accelerate the progress in human rights,
the article said, and meanwhile, it will actively push forward the
healthy development in international human rights progress through
dialogues and cooperation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
