<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Business Network, China to Launch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 12 (Xinhua) -- A San Francisco-based U.S.
enterprise announced Monday that it has signed exclusive
co-branding and revenue-sharing arrangements with China to promote
import and export growth through an e-commerce portal.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Business Network, Inc., founded early last year to help
pioneer Internet services in China, said that the arrangements
were signed with six Chinese governmental ministries, and the
portal called "MeetChina.com" will connect the rest of the world
to the vast resources of China.
</P>
<P>
The first vertical market to be represented by the portal will
be the burgeoning Chinese electronics industry, said the Network,
quoting the Chinese Ministry of Information Industry as saying
that the portal is expected to play a significant role in boosting
China's growing export economy by allowing its manufacturers to
deal with foreign buyers directly.
</P>
<P>
Also participating will be one of the key investors in the new
portal, Pacific Technology Venture Fund-China, Inc. -- the venture
capital subsidiary of IDG, the world's leading IT media, research
and exposition company -- and Critical Path, Inc., one of the
world's leading Internet messaging technology companies.
</P>
<P>
The MeetChina.com Web site plans to offer the resources of over
15,000 Chinese electronics companies by the end of July, according
to U.S. Business Network. Other key Chinese industries are
scheduled to go online with the portal later this year.
</P>
<P>
"This revolutionary promotion center and electronic gateway
will allow foreign mass merchandisers to have rapid and direct
access to multiple categories of Chinese electronics products and
companies," said the network company.
</P>
<P>
MeetChina.com will initially host, design and promote the Web
sites of Chinese companies, said the Network, and as the promotion
center expands its activities this year, both sides will share
revenue through transaction brokerage fees, advertising sales and
membership dues.
</P>
<P>
The site is being designed by Total Creative/Skyrocket of San
Francisco. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990413.0350 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Bombs Yugoslav Passenger Train, 10 Dead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GRDALICA VILLAGE, Southern Yugoslavia, April 12 (Xinhua) --
NATO missiles hit a passenger train in broad daylight Monday in
southern Yugoslavia, killing 10 people and wounding 16 others.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses said a NATO plane fired two missiles at a
four-carriage train and another two at a highway above the railway
line at 11:40 (0940 GMT) near the village 260 kilometers southeast
of Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
Nine people died in the raid and the body of the 10th victim
was recovered later from the South Morava River below. More bodies
were feared washed away in the water, local authorities said.
</P>
<P>
Of the 16 wounded, a female dentist from Nis was in critical
condition, doctors at a hospital in nearby Leskovac said.
</P>
<P>
When a group of reporters arrived at the scene at around 18:00
(1600 GMT), all the bodies were taken away, but fragments of human
brain could still be seen beside the railway base.
</P>
<P>
A blood-soaked cloth was dangling from a window of the skeleton
of a carriage severed into two parts by the blast.
</P>
<P>
The train, originated from Belgrade, was heading for Restovac
via Leskovac and Vranje.
</P>
<P>
The four projectiles, apparently air-to-surface missiles,
damaged the railway bridge that leads up to Greece and the highway
bridge that links Belgrade with Skopje, the Macedonian capital.
</P>
<P>
Windows were shattered and tiles shaken off the roofs of the
village houses nearby.
</P>
<P>
Voinsta Zivojnovic, chief of the regional government, said all
the train's passengers were civilians but that their total was not
known yet.
</P>
<P>
Many of the wounded were suffering from burns in the aftermath
of the fire caused by the bombing.
</P>
<P>
As the bus carrying reporters left Leskovac, the town where the
wounded were treated, air-raid sirens sounded at 20:40 (1840 GMT),
now almost a daily occurrence for most Yugoslav cities as NATO's
bombing campaign against the Balkan country entered the 20th
night. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
