<DOCNO> XIE19990413.0351 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Premier Zhu Leaves for New York </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHICAGO, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji left
here for New York by special plane Monday after a two-day visit to
Chicago, the third largest city in the United States.
</P>
<P>
New York is the fifth stop of his current visit in the United
States, the first visit to the country by a Chinese premier in 15
years.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Chicago, the Chinese premier met with
leaders from several transnational companies such as United
Airlines and Caterpillar Incorporation.
</P>
<P>
They expressed their wish to expand cooperation with China,
especially in the economic field.
</P>
<P>
Premier Zhu also visited a working American farm in the
outskirt of Chicago, the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, an
international market place trading futures and options on futures
on a variety of products, and headquarters of the Motorola, Inc.,
a world-famous communications company. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990413.0352 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chicago Welcomes Chinese Premier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHICAGO, April 12 (Xinhua) -- A luncheon attended by 1,000
distinguished guests was held here Monday to welcome Chinese
Premier Zhu Rongji to Chicago, the fourth leg of his eight-day
trip to the United States.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the luncheon, Lieutenant Governor Corinne Wood of
Illinois told Zhu, "Your visit here today is truly a great honor."
</P>
<P>
The luncheon, which was attended by some business tycoons, U.S.
officials including Secretary of Commerce William Daley and local
officials, was organized by the Mid-America Committee.
</P>
<P>
In his remarks, Zhu expressed his hope that cooperation between
Illinois and China, particularly in agriculture, will be promoted.
</P>
<P>
Despite the unprecedented achievement China has made in
agriculture, the country "still need to cooperate with the rest of
the world including the U.S."
</P>
<P>
Zhu also indicated that the agriculture agreement signed
between China and the U.S. last week serves the interests of both
countries.
</P>
<P>
Wood stressed that China is a nation that has over the last two
decades made substantial progress in opening its markets and
society to the world.
</P>
<P>
Both Wood and Mayor of Chicago Richard Daley expressed their
strong interest in strengthening relations with China.
</P>
<P>
"Not only do many Chinese-Americans in the Chicago area want us
to build a greater bridge with China, people all across the great
city recognize China's importance to our economy," the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
"In addition, they admire China's rich cultural heritage that
they rarely get a chance to experience," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The People's Republic of China is tremendously important to
Illinois and Illinois is important to... China," Wood said in her
remarks.
</P>
<P>
She said that the people of Illinois look forward to working
with Chinese people as partners and friends in the world
community.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese premier urged the American businessmen to seize the
opportunity in China.
</P>
<P>
"China is a huge market with tremendous potentials. The
friendly relations and cooperation between China and the United
States will bring tangible and boundless benefit to both peoples,"
Zhu added.
</P>
<P>
Zhu urged the guests to use their influence to support China's
entry into the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
Zhu and U.S. President Bill Clinton last week issued a joint
statement, in which the U.S. side committed itself to strongly
supporting China's entry into the WTO in 1999.
</P>
<P>
In his remarks at the luncheon, Secretary Daley, who is the
brother of Mayor Daley, reiterated the position of the Clinton
administration.
</P>
<P>
"It is good for China, it is good for the America and it is
good for the world trade," said the secretary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
